<1ST_LINE>u a AM-RagingWatersFire     09-05 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Raging Waters Fire,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Near Aquatic Park Destroys Eight Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIMAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire Monday near an aquatic park that
boasts ``five million gallons'' burned about 10 acres of brush
before it was extinguished, and destroyed eight cars, authorities
said.
   Firefighters had some difficulty in controlling the fire at
first because ``there's no fire hydrant in the parking lot. We
can't get any water to the cars,'' Los Angeles County fire
Inspector John Lenihan said.
   County fire Capt. Garry Oversby said later that water was
rerouted from hydrants nearby.
   It was not immediately known whether the blaze began in a
vehicle or on the vegetation in Bonnelli Park, but the flames
leaped from car to car, Oversby said.
   The fire was reported shortly after 2 p.m. in an overflow
parking area for Raging Waters amusement park less than one mile
away. The park was not evacuated and no one was injured.
   ``Raging Waters is 44 acres, five million gallons and tons of
fun for everyone,'' said a tape-recorded message at the park, about
25 miles northeast of Los Angeles. The park features 12 water
slides, a fresh-water surf pool, and a river-rafting ride.
   Damage was estimated at $50,000, Oversby said.
</TEXT>
