<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 2351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Carlucci     09-05 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Carlucci,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official says China is not a major arms dealer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's top military official, speaking to
reporters Tuesday before meeting with U.S. Defense Secretary Frank
Carlucci, said China is not a major arms dealer.
   ``China is a developing country. China can only sell a little.
It is only a small fraction of what the United States has sold,''
Defense Minister Qin Jiwei said.
   China's sales of missiles to Middle East nations, including
Silkworm missiles to Iran, have been criticized by the United
States.
   According to U.S. figures, China sold about $2 billion worth of
arms last year, mainly to developing countries. China does not
provide information on its arms sales.
   Qin said China and other Third World countries sell only
conventional arms ``but the United States is selling advanced arms
such as the F-16'' jet fighter. ``We can't compare the two kinds of
arms,'' he said.
   Deputy Chief of Staff Xu Xin, also talking to reporters in the
Great Hall of the People, insisted China strictly regulates its
arms sales. ``First, they are for defense. Second, they are for
maintaining stability and peace, not war,'' he said.
   Earlier Tuesday the American national anthem echoed off the gray
walls of the Chinese Military Museum as China's top military
leaders welcomed Carlucci on his first official visit.
   Carlucci, accompanied by Qin, reviewed a 120-member honor guard
from the People's Liberation Army.
   Carlucci arrived Monday for a five-day visit to discuss
international and bilateral issues.
   China is expected to call on the United States to remove
restrictions on technology transfers and approve export licenses
for U.S. companies wanting to use Chinese Long March missiles to
launch satellites.
   Use of the Chinese missiles has been opposed by U.S. defense
officials concerned about giving China access to U.S. satellite
technology.
   Regional conflicts in Afghanistan and Cambodia and the Soviet
military stance in the Far East are also likely to be discussed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
