<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 2356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Food-Arrests 2ndLd-Writethru a0652 09-05 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Food-Arrests, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0652,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dozens Arrested Trying To Distribute Free Food</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after fourth `It was...' with advocacy group
giving city an ``award.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty people were arrested Monday when a
group trying to distribute free food and leaflets scuffled with
police, who had previously warned the group to get a permit or move
elsewhere.
   A television cameraman was injured when a police officer knocked
him to the ground at the fracas on the edge of Golden Gate Park.
   Food and fists went flying when a squad of police officers
wearing riot gear closed in on about 200 people gathered for the
``Food Not Bombs'' give-away.
   It was the second time in a week the group had clashed with
police. On Aug. 29, 29 people were arrested in a similar
confrontation. Group leaders said they will return each Monday.
   Later Monday in Warwick, Mass., a group active on behalf of the
homeless, the Gandhi Peace Center, gave its annual Marie Antoinette
Award for Community Consciousness to the city of San Francisco to
recognize the arrests. The tongue-in-cheek award refers to the
French queen's famous remark of, ``Let them eat cake,'' when told
the peasants were without bread.
   The latest confrontation took place about 45 minutes after the
group marched into the southeast corner of the park, adjacent to
the Haight-Ashbury district, popular in the 1960s among hippies and
in the '80s among people who buy and restore Victorian homes.
Police moved in as the group's members began giving food to one
another.
   Police spokesman Sgt. Jerry Senkir said it was considered an
illegal give-away after food was given to 25 people.
   As the officers approached, food began to fly through the air.
One officer was hit in the face with a plate of rice and another
was struck in the neck with a tomato.
   A police officer grabbed KPIX cameraman Hank Schoepp, knocking
him to the ground. The cameraman lay stunned for a few moments with
blood trickling from his cheek and his camera tossed aside. He then
got up and resumed filming the clash.
   Some of those arrested were dragged away with their wrists bound
by plastic ties. They were loaded into police vans and taken away.
Senkir said they faced a possible misdemeanor count of creating a
nuisance and two park infractions: illegal distribution of food and
illegal leafleting.
   The park infractions carry a maximum penalty of a $50 fine.
   Senkir said one woman also faced a charge of assaulting an
officer.
   Senkir said the giveaway would not be illegal if the group had
obtained permits. He said the group had been offered other sites
for the give-away, but rejected that idea.
   The group had 15 to 20 cartons of food, including bread,
carrots, lettuce, rice, melons and corn.
   The leaflets said the group had been harassed in recent months
by police and had been unfairly characterized by Mayor Art Agnos as
being interested in exploiting the homeless and hungry.
   Patrisha Vestey, who was handing out deviled eggs, said she was
a legal assistant in a law office and lived in the neighborhood.
``I disapproved of what the police are doing. I think the poor
should be taken care of,'' she said. It was not clear if she was a
member of the group.
   Lorraine Rorke, vice president of Stanyan-Fulton Association,
said, ``I'm against this particular give-away in this particular
location.
   ``I also feel that they are not so interested in giving away
food as they are in promoting their particular message,'' said Ms.
Rorke, whose organization is one of several neighborhood
associations opposed to the ``Food Not Bombs'' give-aways.
   ``It's a free country, and if they want to have their political
views, they can have them. I just don't like their means of using
the hungry and blocking the entrance to the park,'' she said.
</TEXT>
