<DOCNO> AP880905-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 0017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-IRA     09-05 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-IRA,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Long-Awaited Inquest Into Gibraltar IRA Deaths To Begin</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When three Irish Republican Army members were
gunned down in Gibraltar on March 6 while allegedly plotting a car
bombing, the British government claimed a victory on the
battlefield of terrorism.
   Instead it got a political controversy that is still simmering
six months later. A long-awaited inquest into the killings opens
Tuesday in the British colony on the southeast tip of Spain.
   Mairead Farrell, Daniel MacCann and Sean Savage were unarmed
when they died. The car bomb, much to the British government's
embarrassment, never materialized, although the IRA admitted the
three were on a guerrilla mission and a car full of explosives was
found 40 miles from the scene two days later.
   Moreover, two British television networks investigating what had
happened that sunny Sunday in Gibraltar found witnesses whose
accounts strongly suggested the three were shot without being given
any chance to surrender.
   It all boiled down to a simple question that confronts every
democracy facing a terrorist threat: Did Britain bend the rule of
law?
   Critics like Amnesty International, the human rights watchdog,
which demanded an inquiry into the shootings in hopes of answering
that question, were rebuffed by Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher,
who said she was outraged that the question was even being asked.
   As far as the government was concerned, a disaster was averted.
It argued that there was no way of knowing on that day that no car
bomb was in Gibraltar; that it had to be assumed a bomb was set to
blow up a military parade and hordes of onlookers; that there was
no certainty the perpetrators were not armed and did not have
remote-control detonators to explode the bomb the moment they were
told to surrender.
   The government sought to dissuade Thames Television and the
British Broadcasting Corp. from broadcasting the documentaries,
arguing that ``trial by TV'' would prejudice the inquest.
   The broadcasts went ahead, confronting viewers with some
chilling accounts from witnesses.
   Stephen Bullock, a lawyer, told the BBC he ``saw a chap with a
white shirt reeling backward, with a man standing four feet away
from him, firing a gun constantly and following him down as he
fell.''
   He said: ``It wasn't a question of just putting one or two shots
into him just to stop him. It seemed to me this was a deliberate
shooting to kill, no question.''
   The BBC also quoted an unidentified witness who saw Sean Savage
on his back, with another man standing over him with his foot on
his chest.
   ``I heard no warning before the shots were fired,'' she was
quoted as saying. ``He continued to fire shots into the man as he
lay on the ground.''
   Carmen Proetta, watching from her apartment, said she believed
Mairead Farrell and Daniel McCann had their hands up in surrender
when they were shot dead by a man who ``went into a crouch position
and took deliberate aim at them.''
   The issues have been debated since 1982, when police in Northern
Ireland killed five unarmed suspects and an innocent youth in three
separate incidents. The arguments arose anew after three IRA men
were gunned down in a British army ambush in the west of the
province last Tuesday.
   Defending the government in the right-wing Daily Express after
the TV documentaries, Lord Chalfont denounced any ``equivalence
between indiscriminate killing in the course of political
terrorism, and the killing of terrorists by security forces engaged
in counterterrorist operations.''
   The liberal Guardian, on the other hand, maintained: ``A state
that turns to terror itself in desperate recourse'' in the end
endorses values of terrorists.
   Tuesday's inquest, which was postponed from June, is now the
focus of attention. Sixty-five witnesses have been called, and
Gibraltar is in a state of high alert, wracked by frequent bomb
scares.
   The seven operatives involved in the March 6 incident are
thought to belong to the army's Special Air Services, a top-secret
anti-terrorist team, and they will testify behind a screen to
prevent their being marked for reprisals.
   But the British government has reserved the right to keep them
away from the inquest.
   If the 11-member jury returns a verdict of unlawful killings,
Attorney General Eric Thistlethwaite of Gibraltar will prosecute
the perpetrators, according to high-level sources in the colony who
requested anonymity.
   The mainly Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
Northern Ireland and unite the Protestant-dominated province with
the Republic of Ireland under socialist rule.
</TEXT>
