<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 0020EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CocaineFreighter     09-05 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cocaine Freighter,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Intercepts Cocaine-Laden Colombian Freighter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard fired warning shots at a
cocaine-laden freighter heading into St. John in the U.S. Virgin
Islands and arrested five crewmen who said they were Colombian
nationals, a spokesman said Sunday night.
   The freighter She-Me turned around and fled U.S. territorial
waters about 7:30 p.m. EDT Saturday after the Coast Guard cutter
Nunivak ordered it to stop, said Coast Guard Lt. John Felker in
Miami.
   Narrowly avoiding several collisions in an attempt to intercept
the freighter, the cutter received permission from Coast Guard
headquarters in Washington, D.C., to fire warning shots across the
freighter's bow, Felker said.
   ``Under the doctrine of hot pursuit, he was still in territorial
seas,'' Felker said. ``He was approximately nine or 10 miles off
St. John when the warning shots were fired, and the vessel was
seized.''
   Felker said 1,000 pounds of cocaine, hidden in a secret
compartment, were seized, and five crewmen were taken into custody
at San Juan, Puerto Rico.
   Felker said authorities were still trying to determine the
She-Me's country of origin and registry Sunday night.
   The seizure was aided by intelligence information from the
National Narcotics and Border Interdiction Service, headed by Vice
President George Bush, Felker said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
