<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names SUB a0414 09-05 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names, SUB, a0414,0390</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS item on Tyson to lead with 5 grafs to UPDATE with
identity of car; witness reporting Tyson seemed to have been
knocked unconscious; picks up 3rd graf pvs, `Tyson, who ...';
Longer version moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavyweight boxing champion Mike Tyson is
recuperating today from minor head and chest injuries after
apparently being knocked out in a single-car accident near his
upstate training camp.
   Tyson's BMW apparently skidded on a wet road Sunday morning,
said a spokesman for the boxer, Dan Klores, who gave no other
details of the crash.
   A witness said the accident occurred while Tyson was driving his
car out of the yard at his adopted family's home in Catskill and it
skidded and slammed into a tree. He was found, apparently
unconscious.
   ``Mike was just leaning back in his car seat and I took his
pulse,'' said Yvonne Conrad, a niece of Camille Ewald, whom Tyson
has been close to since he began training in Catskill eight years
ago.
   ``He was normal, his breathing wasn't heavy or labored. I didn't
hear anything wrong with him. We just couldn't arouse him. We tried
to wake him up by asking `Mike, Mike,' and we just couldn't get
anything from him.''
   Tyson, who was recovering from a broken bone in his right hand
suffered in a street fight two weeks ago with heavyweight Mitch
Green, was taken to two upstate hospitals before being transferred
Sunday night to Columbia Presbyterian Medical Center here.
   Tyson was hospitalized for observation and diagnostic tests,
said Dr. Carolyn Britton of Columbia Presbyterian. ``He suffered
minor trauma to the head and the chest wall,'' Britton said, adding
that Tyson's condition was stable. ``He's neurologicallly normal.''
   As Tyson arrived in New York City, his wife, actress Robin
Givens, tried to keep waiting photographers away from her husband.
   As cameramen pressed forward, Givens pushed them back, shouting,
``Give him a break.''
   Tyson, whose championship bout against British champ Frank Bruno
was recently postponed until Oct. 22 because of the hand injury,
was scheduled to accompany his wife to the Soviet Union on
Wednesday.
   In his last fight in the ring on June 27, Tyson knocked out
previously unbeaten Michael Spinks in 91 seconds, earning $22
million.
</TEXT>
