<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PetCroc     09-05 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pet Croc,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bite A Mistake, Owner Vows To Keep Pet Croc At Arms Length</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 71-year-old retiree whose pet
crocodile bit off his arm was reunited with ``Charlene'' today and
said he'd keep her _ at his other arm's length.
   ``Its marvellous having her back,'' said Alf Casey. ``The
separation hasn't changed us.''
   Casey told the Melbourne Sun newspaper he thought his 23-year
friendship with Charlene, a 6{-foot saltwater croc, was doomed when
she bit the arm that fed her.
   Wildlife officers had wanted to shoot the reptile but Casey's
family intervened and Charlene was exiled to a crocodile farm in
Queensland.
   ``It was my fault. I asked her if she wanted some fish and I put
my hand in the bucket and didn't give her a fish,'' Casey said.
``All she could think about was the fish and with my hand being
there she bit it.''
   Despite losing his right arm and spending three weeks in the
hospital after the November 1986 attack, Casey said he always
wanted Charlene back.
   ``I must admit I do keep her at arms length now, but I get in
the pen with her and give her a bit of a scratch,'' he said.
   Casey used to take Charlene on family outings and to the local
pub until she got too heavy to handle, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
