<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 0204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     09-05 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Metropolitan Sanitary District of Greater
Chicago is trying to clean up its image with a new name, but it's
doubtful employees will want to be known as ``sludge-busters'' or
``scummy can cleaners.''
   ``People hear `sanitary' and they think `garbage,''' said James
Kirie, the district's finance commissioner. ``But we reclaim and
purify water and control floods _ that's our job.''
   Kirie, 77, decided to hold a contest to find a better moniker
and is personally offering a $1,000 first prize for the best name.
He said he has wanted to change the name for nearly two decades.
   Letters, poems, and dummy logos _ scrawled in crayon or
professionally typeset _ have spelled out clever and not-so-clever
suggestions.
   ``Metropolitan Sludge-Buster Treatment Department,'' ``Groovy
and Pure Channel District,'' ``Cook County Waters `R' Us,'' and
``Scummy Can Cleaners'' were among the suggestions.
   Some came up with names that suggested a theme park:
``Clearwater County,'' ``Neptune's Angels,'' and ``Everything
Water.''
   One woman thought ``Aqua Fix'' captured the essence of the
department, while one man thought ``Washers of Water (WOW)'' summed
it up best.
   Commissioners will narrow the list of possibilities this week,
Kirie said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Bud Clark says the ``Dress As You
Please Day'' is no longer a fashion hit and decided not to observe
the day of casual attire this year.
   Clark proclaimed a day for casual dress his first year as mayor
and drew nationwide attention. Similar observances followed in 1986
and 1987, but fewer and fewer downtown workers took part.
   Clark's top aide, Charles P. Duffy, says there's simply been no
demand for it this year.
   ``If people really wanted it, we'd do it, but we've only had one
phone call asking about it,'' Duffy said last week.
   Some events are just one-time happenings, Duffy said, ``and
Dress As You Please Day probably should have been one of them.''
   But former police chief Ron Still, Clark's challenger in this
fall's election, insists Clark dropped the event this year in an
effort to present a more conservative image to the electorate.
   Though the official observance of casual dress may be dead, some
employees keep it alive at City Hall, where air conditioning is
unknown.
   The city auditor allows shorts in the office when the mercury
tops 90 degrees, as it did last week.
</TEXT>
