<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 0208EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NorthKorea     09-05 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-North Korea,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Kim Il Sung's Second Son Named Envoy To Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korean President Kim Il Sung's second son was
recently appointed ambassador to Hungary to avoid a possible
leadership threat to his older brother, a Japanese news agency
reported.
   Kyodo News Service on Sunday quoted unidentified Japanese
government officials as saying they had learned from Eastern
European sources that Kim Pyong Il, 34, was director-general of the
North Korean people's armed forces bureau before being named
ambassador.
   It quoted the sources as saying Kim Il Sung's oldest son and
designated successor, Kim Jong Il, 46, was having problems dealing
with the nation's stagnant economy the Olympic Games, which begin
this month in rival South Korea. North Korea has demanded to
co-host the games.
   Because of Kim Jong Il's leadership problems, the sources said,
people were beginning to favor Kim Pyong Il.
   Kim Jong Il is secretary of the ruling communist Workers' Party
of Korea.
   Kim Pyong Il was ``was taken out of the country tactfully
because the people's interest in him might cause problems for the
question of succession,'' Kyodo quoted the Japanese sources as
saying.
   Kyodo said Kim Pyong Il is the offspring of Kim Il Sung and his
present wife, Kim Song Ai, while Kim Jong Il is the son of the
North Korean leader's late wife, Kim Chong Sook.
   Kim Pyong Il had been in the military since graduating from Kim
Il Sung University, the state university named after his father,
Kyodo said.
   Japanese Foreign Ministry officials were not immediately
available for comment on the report.
   Kim Il Sung, 76, has ruled North Korea for nearly four decades.
He became premier in 1948, commanded North Korean forces in the
1950-53 Korean War and was named president in 1972.
   North Korea is considered one of the world's most closed
societies and Kim has established himself as the object of a
personality cult.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
