<DOCNO> AP880905-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 0213EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--CrabRace     09-05 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Crab Race,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Crab Wins The Race After Competitors Die En Route</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRISFIELD, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The competition would have been stiffer in
the Governor's Cup Race for speedy crabs, were it not for the fact
that a few of the scuttlers arrived in a stiff state themselves.
   A one-clawed blue crab named Sutter's Gold, representing
California Gov. George Deukmejian, won the race during the 41st
annual National Hard Crab Derby & Fair on Saturday.
   Sutter's Gold scrambled to victory in the 16-foot inclined
wooden course in slightly more than one minute.
   Alaska's entrant, a king crab more than 4 feet from claw to
claw, dubbed ``King Louis the 49th,'' died in overnight mail from
Anchorage.
   ``The winners need to sit down and enjoy him, that's what he
would have wanted,'' a spokeswoman for Alaska Gov. Steve Cowper
said of King Louis' death. ``Just throw the butter in a pan and go
for it!''
   A team of Dungeness crabs flown in from Washington state also
died before post time.
</TEXT>
