<DOCNO> AP880905-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 0232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashigtonInBrief     09-05 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washigton In Brief,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says Sweatshops Not A Thing Of The Past</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government report says sweatshops, thought
to be a thing of the past in American labor, continue to exist in
the United States.
   The General Accounting Office report released Sunday cited
restaurants and related businesses, apparel manufacturing and
meat-processing industries as the worst offenders.
   ``I think most Americans believe sweatshops vanished generations
ago, but they are here today, in all parts of the country,'' said
Rep. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., who had requested the study, in a
statement released with the report.
   Schumer also said he supported the report's conclusion that
penalties for labor law violations must be increased to deter
abuses.
   The report, based on interviews with 100 state and local
officials nationwide between January and May 1988, said restaurant
and apparel sweatshops were more likely to be populated by
Hispanics and Asians workers.
   The report also cited some of the same reasons for multiple
labor-law violations that were given in the 19th century: a large
immigrant work force and low profit margins in labor-intensive
industries.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Former Members of Congress Reap Big Retirement Benefits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A taxpayers group says that more and more
former members of Congress will become millionaires in retirement.
   The National Taxpayers Union said Sunday former Rep. Ben Reifel
of South Dakota joins a former Maine senator this month as the
first members of Congress to receive $1 million in government
retirement pay.
   ``While most Americans can only dream of a million dollars in
retirement income, dozens of retired legislators will soon become
pension millionaires,'' said David Keating, executive vice
president of the taxpayers group, in a news release.
   Keating said Reifel will receive a September pension check for
$6,966, giving the former five-term Republican more than $1 million
since he retired from Congress in 1971.
   In May, former Republican Sen. Margaret Chase Smith became the
first senator to get a millionaire pension, said Keating.
   Congressional retirement pay is derived from a formula that
includes the average congressional salary over the last three
years, and the group predicted that a proposed increase in
congressional pay to $135,000 next year would greatly increase the
number of million-dollar pensions.
</TEXT>
