<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SuspendedAnimation     09-05 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Suspended Animation,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman In Suspended Animation For Nearly Hour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 76-year-old woman was placed in suspended
animation nearly an hour as surgeons removed an egg-sized aneurysm
from the base of her brain, hospital officials said.
   Cecilia Duffy of Pittsburgh remained comatose Sunday and listed
in critical condition, four days after the unusual operation, said
Judy Secreto, an Allegheny General Hospital spokeswoman.
   ``It's not uncommon for it to last a couple of days,'' Ms.
Secreto said.
   Surgeons removed the aneurysm from Ms. Duffy's brain after
dropping her body temperature by 40 degrees and draining the blood
from her body. Her heart was stopped during Wednesday's operation.
   The coma was induced by barbiturates to protect the brain while
blood flow was suspended, said Ms. Secreto.
   Dr. Julian E. Bailes, a neurosurgeon, said Ms. Duffy fit the
legal criteria for brain death during the 51{ minutes of suspended
animation.
   The aneurysm, a bubble in the blood vessel caused by weakness in
the vessel wall, was suctioned out while Ms. Duffy was on the
bypass machine.
   Any more pressure by the aneurysm would have compressed on the
vital centers of the brain stem, and her heart would have stopped
or she would have gone into a coma and died, Bailes said.
   ``I'm still worried about her but, objectively speaking, there
is a good chance she may pull through this thing,'' he said.
   Post-surgical scans showed increased brain activity, and Ms.
Duffy was moving her legs when touched, according to Bailes. But,
he said, ``There's such a fine line between a perfect outcome and
her never waking up. That's the hard thing.''
   Ms. Duffy had become almost completely disabled during the past
year because of the aneurysm.
   Bailes initially had recommended that Ms. Duffy go to the Barrow
Neurological Institute in Phoenix, Ariz., where he learned the
procedure before coming to Pittsburgh in July. She did not want to
leave Pittsburgh, however.
   Dr. Robert F. Spetzler, director of the Barrow institute, and
six colleagues published an article on the technique in June in The
Journal of Neurosurgery. Of the seven cases cited, all but one
patient survived and four had ``excellent'' results. The two other
survivors reported some weakness but otherwise did well.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
