<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 0438EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-05 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Fall In Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both the dollar and stock prices lost ground in
cautious trading in Tokyo today.
   The dollar opened at 136.25 yen, down 0.50 yen from Friday's
close, and then declined further to end the day at 136.03 yen, down
0.72 yen. The U.S. currency ranged between 135.95 yen and 136.35
yen, with spot trading estimated at $4.4 billion.
   It was the first day-to-day decline in the dollar in Tokyo since
last Monday.
   Foreign exchange traders were in a cautious mood because the New
York market was closed for the Labor Day holiday, said a dealer
with Mitsubishi Bank in Tokyo.
   ``In addition, today is Monday, when trading usually gets
cautious, which makes it even harder for investors to figure out
which direction the market is going to go,'' he said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   ``That's why the dollar-yen exchange rate changed frequently
within a narrow range,'' he added.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which gained 371.75 points during Saturday's
half-day session, lost 146.67 points, or 0.53 percent, closing at
27,341.58.
   Although the Nikkei index opened the day strongly, it then
reversed directions as trading slowed down.
   ``The dollar-yen rate, which is getting stable, and the
increased U.S. jobless rate made investors less worried about
inflation, but they couldn't be completely optimistic yet,'' said
Yoshio Shimoyama of Nikko Securities.
   ``After the active trading in the early morning, some investors
started selling stocks for profit-taking, which was another reason
that prices went down,'' he said.
   But he said the market was regaining its strength as unfavorable
external factors disappeared. ``The market just needs a little more
energy. But share prices usually don't rise much the day after a
big rebound anyway,'' he added.
   Trading on the market's first section was thin, with an
estimated 500 million shares changing hands, compared with the 524
million shares traded during the half day Saturday.
   Among issues losing ground were steels and electricals.
</TEXT>
