<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HairPrank     09-05 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hair Prank,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Telephone Caller Persuades Woman To Cut Off Hair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A telephone caller posing as a hospital
employee persuaded a woman to cut off her hair after tricking her
with a false tale of possible exposure to toxic chemicals.
   Lisa Hansen said Sunday she was ``spooked'' by the incident and
had temporarily moved out of her home here.
   ``Let's hope the police do something about it,'' she said.
   Ms. Hansen, 21, reported the incident to authorities Saturday.
She bought a $60 wig to cover her shorn locks.
   ``He kept saying, `Be sure to cut close to the scalp, so we get
a good test,''' Ms. Hansen said.
   The man, who claimed to work for Mandan Hospital, told Ms.
Hansen she might have been exposed to toxic polychlorinated
biphenyls, or PCBs, through her former husband, a truck driver who
sometimes hauls chemicals.
   Bradley Hansen had already been admitted to the hospital for
tests, some of which confirmed the contamination, the caller told
Ms. Hansen. When Ms. Hansen asked to speak to Hansen she was told
he was still groggy from sedation.
   Ms. Hansen then told the caller she wanted to go to the
hospital, but the caller told her she was ``under quarantine'' and
would have to cut samples of her hair at home, which the state
health department would collect later.
   After she finished cutting her hair, the caller told Ms. Hansen
it was a hoax, she said.
   Mary Ellen Rebenitsch, a hospital spokeswoman, said Sunday the
hospital does not have an employee by the name the caller used.
</TEXT>
