<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Air Show, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0480,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>52nd Person Dies From Ramstein Disaster Injuries</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 10 grafs after 6th pvs, `Of that ...' to UPDATE with
seven Americans hospitalized in good condition, identifications. No
pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RAMSTEIN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 52nd person died from severe
injuries suffered from the fiery air show disaster at the U.S. Air
Force Base in Ramstein, a West German official said today.
   Juergen Dietzen, spokesman for the Rhineland-Palatinate state
government, said the West German died Sunday, but had no other
details.
   Dietzen said the 52 who had died in the Aug. 28 disaster
included 45 West Germans, the three Italian pilots killed in the
mid-air collision that began the disaster, two Americans and a
French and a Dutch citizen.
   The American victims were a U.S. Army private and her 9-year-old
son.
   Dietzen said 164 people remained hospitalized from injuries
sustained when an Italian air force stunt team jet collided with
two other jets and crashed in flames into the a crowd of spectators.
   Of that number, ``10 of them are in life-threatening or very
serious condition,'' Dietzen said.
   Meanwhile, seven Americans hospitalized at the U.S. Army
hospital in nearby Landstuhl are in good condition, a hospital
spokeswoman said.
   ``All seven of them are in good condition. They're able to sit
up and talk,'' Landstuhl hospital spokeswoman Marie Shaw said.
   Ms. Shaw could not say when the patients, still being treated
for burn injuries, would be released. She identified the patients
as:
   _Sonya Fuller, 25, of Cheyenne, Wyo., wife of Airman Jeff
Fuller, who is assigned to the 66th Security Police Squadron at
Sembach Air Force Base.
   _William Granflor, 9, son of Sgt. Guillermo Granflor of San
Gabriel, Calif., who is assigned to the 86th Component Repair
Squadron at the Ramstein Air Base.
   _Sgt. Karl Heilig, 31, of San Antonio, Texas. Heilig is assigned
to the 86th Equipment Maintenance Squadron at Ramstein.
   _Lisa A. Newton, 18, daughter of Sgt. Leon Newton, who is
assigned to the U.S. Army's 32nd Support Command at Worms. No U.S.
hometown was given for Miss Newton.
   _Roberta Nicks, 26, of Pittsburgh, Pa., wife of Army Sgt. Lonzo
Nicks, who is assigned to the 11th Signal Battalion, Kleber
Kaserne, Kaiserslautern.
   _David Olson, 21, son of Maj. Steven Olson of Marinette, Wis.,
who is assigned to the 86th Tactical Fighter Wing at Ramstein.
   _Army Sgt. Alexander Tirona, 27, of Cavite, the Philippines,
assigned to the 44th Signal Battalion, Kleber Kaserne,
Kaiserslautern.
</TEXT>
