<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Governors     09-05 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Governors,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Governors Appeal For Japanese Investment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three governors met with Japanese officials today
and appealed for more Japanese investment in their states to help
with economic hardship.
   Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton, Louisiana Gov. Buddy Roemer and
Mississipi Gov. Ray Mabus said their states had been hit by
declines in manufacturing and the oil industry, but were rich in
assets that the Japanese need.
   The three Democrats met with Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita to
urge increased Japanese investment, and also met with officials of
the Japan External Trade Organization, the Japan-Southern U.S.
Association, and officials of the Export-Import Bank of Japan.
   Roemer said the tri-state region is rich in oil and natural gas,
timber, agricultural products and seafood, all products Japan needs
and that can be transported through the states' six seaports.
   Clinton said the states are interested in attracting Japanese
chemical, electronics and auto parts manufacturers. Although the
three states already attract more than $20 billion in foreign
investments _ most of it from Canada and Europe _ almost none comes
from Japan.
   Mabus said Mississipi is offering incentives such as property
tax exemptions, low-interest or no-interest loans and tax credits
for high-technology jobs.
   ``We can build roads, railroads, and ports at state expense. We
have a number of buildings ready to be leased or purchased,'' he
added.
   Clinton said Arkanasas was willing to pay air fares for workers
to travel to Japan to retrain, if necessary.
   The unemploylment rate is 7.2 percent in Arkansas, 7.5 percent
in Mississippi, and 11 percent in Louisiana.
</TEXT>
