<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0488,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Along Two Cold Fronts In East Half of Nation; West Hot, Dry</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with temperatures in Los
Angeles, San Diego. Picks up in 6th graf, `A snowplow ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two cold fronts scattered rain in the eastern half of the nation
today but most of the West was hot and dry. A downtown temperature
of 110 degrees tied the hottest day ever recorded in Los Angeles.
   Hawaii was out from under tropical storm alerts and hail piled
so deep in Wisconsin that a snowplow was put into service.
   Rainfall subsided in the deep South early today after as much as
5 inches of rain fell in sections of Alabama during the weekend.
   A tropical storm watch was canceled in the Hawaiian Islands as
Hurricane Uleki moved westward away from the islands, weakening
gradually.
   Hot, dry weather continued in much of California and the
Northwest, with several record highs on Sunday. The 110-degree
reading in Los Angeles tied a record set Sept. 1, 1955, the hottest
day in the city's history. The temperature at San Diego's Lindbergh
Field reached 107 degrees, breaking a 1961 record for the date.
   A snowplow was dispatched to clear hail from three intersections
as a Labor Day weekend storm deposited as much as 18 inches of the
icy stuff on parts of Milwaukee.
   Strong winds from the north later Sunday churned waves to an
estimated 12 feet on the open waters of Lake Michigan, officials
said.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms scattered
ahead of a cold front over the Gulf Coast and Atlantic Coast
region; thunderstorms scattered across Florida; showers developing
ahead of another cold front across Pennsylvania and New York into
New England; cloudy to partly sunny skies over the Great Lakes
states and upper Mississippi Valley; and for mostly sunny skies
elsewhere.
   Highs will be in the 50s in northern Michigan; 60s in much of
the upper Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes states, western
Pennsylvania and New York and northern New England; 90s in the
Florida Peninsula and Pacific Northwest; 100 to 110 in the desert
Southwest; and 70s to 80s in most of the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m EDT ranged from 43
degrees at Grand Forks, N.D., Yellowstone, Wyo., Sault Ste. Marie,
Mich., Wausau, Wis., and Custer, S.D., to 87 at Bakersfield,
Calif., and Phoenix and Yuma, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 63 foggy; Boston 67 cloudy; Buffalo 64
thunderstorms; Charleston, S.C., 73 cloudy; Cincinnati 60 cloudy;
Cleveland 60 showery; Detroit 55 drizzle; Miami 80 fair; New York
70 foggy; Philadelphia 67 rain; Pittsburgh 58 fair; Portland 59
foggy; Washington 70 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 43 fair; Chicago 52 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 65 fair; Denver 52 fair; Des Moines 57 fair;
Indianapolis 60 windy; Kansas City 57 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 49
fair; Nashville 60 fair; New Orleans 74 windy; St. Louis 63 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 60 fair; Anchorage 48 fair; Las Vegas 79
fair; Los Angeles 77 fair; Phoenix 86 partly cloudy; Salt Lake City
64 partly cloudy; San Diego 77 fair; San Francisco 55 fair; Seattle
56 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 63 cloudy; Toronto 52 showery.
</TEXT>
