<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 1009EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Mail     09-05 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Mail,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mail Strike Spreads In Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of British postal workers were
on strike today, halting some 100 million letters and parcels, in a
work stoppage over regional bonuses and the hiring of temporary
workers.
   Alan Tuffin, general secretary of the Union of Communications
Workers, said more than 40,000 of its members in the Post Office
were striking Sunday and the whole system could be brought to a
halt by midweek.
   The Post Office, which employs 140,000 people and handles 51
million items a day, said 28 major city center sorting offices were
on strike, affecting 100 million letters and parcels.
   In affected areas, mail cannot be collected, sorted or
delivered. London, Birmingham, Manchester, Liverpool, Edinburgh and
Glasgow are among the affected cities. Overseas mail has almost
stopped because the two sorting offices which handle it are on
strike.
   The postal strike began Wednesday as a 24-hour walkout to
protest regional pay bonuses _ an issue that remains unresolved.
The strike has continued in various parts of the country to protest
the bonuses and the hiring of temporary workers to clear the
backlog of mail caused by Wednesday's strike.
   The union objects to the Post Office offering weekly bonuses of
7.5 pounds to 20 pounds ($12.52 to $33.40) to recruit workers in
London and southeast England. Those regions are prosperous, and the
postal service has difficulty hiring workers.
   The union said it would not tolerate regional pay differences
and any bonuses should be paid nationally.
</TEXT>
