<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel     09-05 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Moslem Cleric To Be Indicted On Incitement Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said today they plan to indict a Moslem
cleric on incitement charges for allegedly urging worshipers to
fight Jews working at an archaeological dig near two sacred mosques
in Arab east Jerusalem.
   Mohammed Jamal, deputy head of the Supreme Moslem Council, or
Waqf, would be the highest-ranking Moslem official to be tried by
Israel since it captured east Jerusalem in the 1967 Middle East War.
   Since the Dec. 8 start of the Palestinian uprising in the
occupied territories, Israel has jailed at least 20 Moslem
officials, including preachers, teachers and mosque guards.
   In a telephone interview, Jamal told the The Associated Press:
``What I did is not incitement. It is the right of Moslems to come
to their holy place and defend it. I would do this again.''
   The cleric also threatened to ``make trouble'' if he was taken
to court, but he did not elaborate.
   At issue were clashes July 3 in which riot police fired tear gas
and rubber bullets at hundreds of stone-throwing Palestinians
enraged by the archaeological dig near the Temple Mount, known in
Arabic as Haram esh-Sharif. The mount houses two of Islam's holiest
shrines, the Al Aqsa and Dome of the Rock mosques.
   Using mosque loudspeakers, Moslem officials urged Palestinians
to rush to the site and defend the shrines, saying Israelis planned
to dig a tunnel to the Temple Mount.
   Israeli officials denied the charges, saying the dig was
designed to open an underground staircase running along the Western
Wall, Judaism's holiest site. The Western Wall, the last remnant of
the Second Temple, borders the Temple Mount.
   Israeli officials acknowledged they did not coordinate the dig
with the Waqf, and excavations were suspended temporarily.
   Officials now plan to draw up an indictment against Jamal for
his role in the clashes, said Jerusalem police spokesman Rafi Levy.
Police said the charge carries a maximum three-year penalty.
   Levy also confirmed today that Hatem Abdul Khader, managing
editor of the Arabic daily Al Fajr, was arrested and ordered held
for six months without trial. He would not elaborate.
   More than a dozen police officers raided Al Fajr's east
Jerusalem office Sunday night and arrested Khader.
   ``We consider this an illegal step, an aggression against Al
Fajr and all Palestinian journalists,'' said Khaled Abu Aker, one
of the editors of the pro-Palestine Liberation Organization
newspaper.
   Since the beginning of the uprising, dozens of Palestinian
journalists have been detained by Israeli authorities.
</TEXT>
