<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GulfTalks     09-05 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Talks,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Progress Reported In 12th Day of Iran-Iraq Peace Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials today reported no progress in the 12th
day of U.N.-sponsored talks on ending the Iran-Iraq war.
   Spokeswoman Therese Gastaut said U.N. mediator Jan Eliasson
first met late Sunday with the Iraqi side, minus Foreign Minister
Tariq Aziz, and then this morning with the Iranians, likewise
without Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati. While results remain
elusive, ``Work is continuing,'' she said.
   The Iraqi and Iranian foreign ministers have not met since the
second day of the talks. On Saturday, Aziz described the talks as
``still in square one.''
   Meanwhile, foreign ministers of the Gulf Cooperation Council met
today for a second day in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, for discussions
focused on breaking the deadlock in Geneva. The council members are
Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar, Bahrain, Oman and the United Arab
Emirates.
   Saudi Arabia's Al-Sharq Al-Awsat newspaper today quoted council
sources as saying members of the security and economic alliance in
the oil-rich Persian Gulf region ``are serious about entering as
indirect partners in the Geneva negotiations, even if it's in the
final stages.''
   The problems that have bogged down the Geneva talks include
troop withdrawals, freedom of navigation, border questions and the
status of the Shatt al-Arab waterway, Iraq's only outlet to the sea.
   Iran has also called for an inquiry to establish who started the
war, one of the provisions of Security Council Resolution 598,
which is the basis for the Geneva talks.
   Fighting halted Aug. 20 after nearly eight years of fighting
when a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire took effect after Iran
unconditionally accepted Security Council Resolution 598 calling
for a truce.
   Iran says the war started Sept. 22, 1980, when Iraqi troops
invaded Iran. But Iraq marks the anniversary on Sept. 4, when Iran
shelled Iraqi territory.
</TEXT>
