<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-Storm     09-05 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Storm,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>18 Die In Storms</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with five more deaths, CORRECT
attribution of 20,000 homeless, clarify that Kristy affected
Pacific but did not hit coast, other detais. No Pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The confirmed death toll rose to 18 today as
emergency crews worked to open roads and deliver supplies to
communities isolated by flooding after two hurricanes, officials
said.
   The government newspaper El Nacional, citing preliminary
reports, said 27 people died.
   Much of the southern half of the country was affected by
hurricanes Debby and Kristy _ from Veracruz on the east to the west
coast resorts and Chiapas on the border with Guatemala.
   Officials said most of the victims were killed in mudslides or
were swept away by swollen rivers. An estimated 50,000 people were
evacuated from their homes.
   Hurricane Debby struck on Friday. Kristy affected the Pacific
coast for several days, but never hit land and moved out to sea.
   In Veracruz, about 150 miles northeast of Mexico City, about
25,000 people were left homeless, state government spokesman Raul
Torres said Sunday. As many as 10,000 residents of Alamo were
forced to leave their homes, Torres said
   He said three people died in the town of Poza Rica and three in
nearby Papantla.
   In the central state of Hidalgo, a mudslide crushed three houses
in the mountain community of Ixtlahuaco, about 100 miles northeast
of Mexico City, killing four people and injuring 16 others,
according to 2nd Commander Florencio Gutierrez Hernandez, a State
Public Security Department official.
   Three people died while picking corn and tending cattle close to
the banks of flooding rivers in the southern state of Oaxaca, said
Lt. Col. Peregrin Villagomez, assistant public security director.
   On the Pacific coast, five people died in Tapachula, in Chiapas
state at the border with Guatemala, when the Coatan River
overflowed, said Virignia Dorantes, a Red Cross spokeswoman there.
   She said aid was being distributed to those forced to evacuate,
but did not know how many were affected. The government news agency
Notimex said about 20,000 were evacuated in the state.
   Officials said road crews were clearing mud from roads.
   Rain continued to drench the gulf coast and the Pacific coast
from the northwestern state of Sonora south to Jalisco this
morning, the National Weather Service said.
   Streets in parts of Mexico City flooded, choking rush hour
traffic today on some thoroughfares.
   Traffic was moving slowly after 56 mudslides covered a road
between Pachuca and Huejutla, Hernandez said.
   A cracked bridge immobilized traffic for 15 hours over the
weekend on the Pan-American highway near the city of Oaxaca, 230
miles southeast of Mexico City, he said. By late Sunday, automobile
traffic had resumed, he said.
   Tourists were stranded in the resort of Ixtapa-Zihuatenejo,
where the airport was flooded and the road south to Acapulco and
north to Lazaro Cardenas was closed to traffic, hotel owners
reported. They said Ixtapa was left without electricity, and some
hotels ran out of emergency candles.
   Medical teams in Acapulco vaccinated children and urged people
to boil water and take precautions with food to avoid disease.
</TEXT>
