<DOCNO> AP880905-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 1147EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0439 09-05 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0439,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Pays Labor Day Calls on Business as Well as Labor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds. Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Bentsen remarks; picks up
5th graf pvs: Bentsen is.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WACO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, visiting a small business
center on Labor Day, today accused Republican George Bush of
neglecting the needs of Texas and the oil industry he once worked
in.
   The Democratic vice presidential nominee, starting a
cross-country Labor Day trek in his home state, told 250
supporters, ``They've sort of turned their backs on us, this
administration has.''
   Speaking outside a former high school converted with government
and Baylor University funds into the Business Resource Center,
Bentsen said the Republicans ``have an oilman who's running for
president. But frankly I can't remember anything he's done for the
energy industry in the past eight years.''
   Bentsen toured the business center and met with local citizens
trying to revive the struggling economy here in this central Texas
town. He said the start up of new business was important because
Texas ``very much needs that kind of diversification.''
   The Texas senator then planned to fly to Beaumont, Texas, to
speak at a Labor Day picnic, before journeying on to St. Louis and
a joint Labor Day picnic with his running mate, Michael Dukakis.
   Bentsen spokesman Mike McCurry said that in a new campaign
speech crafted last week while Bentsen was on vacation, the
candidate would sound the Democrats' campaign themes of economic
patriotism and fairness.
   Bentsen is stopping in Texas on nearly every campaign trip,
fighting to win the state and its 29 electoral votes for the
Democrats even though Vice President George Bush also calls it home.
   The Democratic Party planned to launch new television spots in
the state this week with the message, ``You can't afford to vote
Republican,'' McCurry said.
   Under an unusual Texas law, Bentsen also is running for
re-election to his Senate seat, which he has held for three terms.
That campaign already has aired advertisements.
   After his two Texas stops, Bentsen was flying this afternoon to
St. Louis, where he was meeting up with Dukakis for a Democratic
Club picnic. Missouri is also a battleground, and Bentsen already
had visited the city twice since being picked for the ticket.
   Bentsen's two-day trip was then picking up the job creation
theme on Tuesday with visits to a job training center in
Lawrenceville, Ga., outside of Atlanta, and Virginia Polytechnic
Institute in Blacksburg, Va., before returning to Washington that
night.
   Bentsen arrived in Waco on Sunday after spending four days
relaxing at a friend's ranch in Wyoming. Bentsen played tennis,
rode horses and went fishing, his staff said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
