<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Hungary     09-05 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Hungary,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Prime Minister May Visit Budapest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir hopes to visit
Budapest this month and told a visiting Hungarian Cabinet minister
he sought better ties between Israel and the East bloc country,
aides said today.
   Shamir spoke in a meeting with the president of Hungary's State
Office for Church Affairs, Imre Miklos, the highest ranking
Hungarian to visit Israel since Hungary broke diplomatic relations
with the Jewish state 21 years ago.
   Miklos, who arrived Sunday for a four-day visit, told Shamir he
hoped the two countries could renew ties ``when the situation
allows,'' Israel radio reported.
   The Hungarian leader said Sunday his trip signalled the start of
a process that could lead to a resumption of diplomatic ties.
``This is a first step and it will be followed by others,'' he told
reporters.
   Hungary, like the Soviet Union and all the East bloc nations
except Romania, severed ties with Israel during the 1967 Middle
East War. Hungary and Israel resumed low-level diplomatic ties last
year and opened interest offices in March.
   Shamir aide Yossi Ahimeir said the prime minister hoped to visit
Budapest later this month but that final plans had not been made.
   Hungary invited Shamir to avoid appearing to be meddling in
Israeli politics, in light of a visit to Budapest in May by
Shamir's rival, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, the radio said.
   In their meeting, Shamir also praised Miklos for Hungary's
``sympathetic and positive'' attitude toward its Jewish community,
said a statement from the prime minister's office.
   Miklos today visited the Yad Vashem memorial to 6 million Jews
slain by the Nazis during World War II and told reporters, ``We
must all ensure that such a tragedy never happens again.''
</TEXT>
