<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 1229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Liberia     09-05 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Liberia,Bjt,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Americans Help Bring Order to Liberia's Financial Chaos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite initial skepticism, U.S. officials are
pleased with an experiment in which 17 American financial experts
moved into Liberian government offices to bring order to the
African nation's chaotic financial system.
   Liberia, a country founded by freed American slaves a century
and a half ago, has always had a special relationship with the
United States, and President Samuel K. Doe turned to Washington in
1987 after his fiscal problems ran out of control.
   Corruption was rampant, government checks were bouncing, civil
servants were being paid months late and bureaucrats were spending
money without regard to budgetary limits. Some government
contractors were not paid for work performed while others received
checks they were not entitled to.
   In January, 1987, when Secetary of State George P. Shultz made a
brief stop in Monrovia, Doe told him, ``I need help.''
   The two countries worked out a plan to put American accountants,
systems managers and computer experts _ recruited by the U.S.
Agency for International Development _ inside the Liberian
bureaucracy.
   The ``operational experts'' _ nicknamed ``Opex'' _ assumed their
duties in January. Nine of the 17 went to the Finance Ministry.
   ``It's worked reasonably well,'' one U.S. official said, summing
up the eight-month-old experiment. ``The benefits have been
considerable already.''
   The official, who insisted on anonymity, said the two-year
program ``has exceeded the expectations of a lot of people who
thought it would never get off the ground.'' Among other benefits,
civil servants are now being paid on time, he said.
   Another official, also speaking anonymously, said, ``Before
there was no government budget. Everything was entirely ad hoc.
Opex has gotten the Liberians to adhere to the budget. It's under
pretty good control but there are still some financial flows
outside the budget.''
   With the Americans co-signing checks and taking over much of
Liberia's economic management, the plan gives the appearance of a
Liberian surrender of sovereignty in a key area, which is a
complaint voiced by Liberian opposition leaders.
   But the State Department says Doe still has the final say on all
financial matters.
   Liberia may be the only country where it would be politically
possible for the United States to play such an intrusive role. But
Liberia, with its red, white and blue flag and its use of the U.S.
dollar as legal tender, has always looked on the United States as a
friend and patron.
   The financial crisis can be traced back about 10 years when the
Liberian government decided to build a $200 million convention
center it couldn't afford. The country fell deeply into debt, and
the problems were compounded in 1980 when Doe, then a 28-year-old
sergeant, took power in a military coup, bringing with him a team
of advisers with no government experience.
   As prices of Liberia's principal exports fell, foreign exchange
earnings dropped. Eventually, because of a poor debt repayment
record, the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund declared
Liberia ineligible for new loans.
   Now, as U.S. officials describe it, Liberia's future seems
brighter, and not only because of Opex. Human rights violations are
down, Liberia's press is once again one of the freest in Africa and
there is increased demand for international demand for latex,
Liberia's major export.
   Concern about AIDS _ acquired immune deficiency syndrome _ has
touched off a boom in sales of latex products, such as condoms and
gloves, contributing to the more upbeat mood these days among
Liberians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880905-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 1233EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Politics Bjt   09-05 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics, Bjt,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor, Likud Platforms Call for Direct Talks with Palestinians</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both major parties have modified their national
election platforms to include support for talks with Palestinians
from the Israeli-occupied territories.
   It is ``a major amendment'' for the right-wing Likud bloc, but
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's political alliance has little
choice because ``Jordan does not appear presently to be a partner
for negotiations,'' Likud legislator Ehud Olmert said in an
interview.
   The center-left Labor Party's new platform also represents a
major shift from its customary position that Israel should
negotiate with King Hussein of Jordan and Palestinians should be
represented in a Jordanian delegation. Labor is led by Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres.
   Hussein forced the platform changes by announcing July 31 that
he would end legal and administrative ties with the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, the Israeli-occupied lands where 1.5 million
Palestinians and 68,000 Jewish settlers live. An uprising against
Israeli rule began in the territories Dec. 8.
   Avraham Burg, a peace activist and Labor candidate for
parliament, said this week the king's decision was a message to
Israelis and Palestinians ``to make up your minds'' on resolving
problems in the West Bank and Gaza, which Israel captured from
Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Another reason for the platform changes appears to be Israel's
desire to pre-empt any Palestine Liberation Organization effort to
assume Jordan's role in the territories.
   Likud and Labor have maintained a tenuous coalition since 1984
because neither party won a majority that year in the 120-seat
Knesset, Israel's parliament. How to resolve the conflict with the
Palestinians has become a central factor in each side's effort to
win control in the election Nov. 1.
   The uprising, in which nearly 260 Palestinians have been killed,
is the most sustained revolt to date against Israeli occupation and
lends extra urgency to the campaign. Four Israelis also have been
slain.
   In the past, the Likud linked criteria for peace talks to the
U.S.-brokered Camp David agreement of 1978, which led to the 1979
peace treaty between Egypt and Israel.
   The agreement called for Egypt, Jordan and Israel to negotiate
an autonomous Palestinian government in the occupied lands, with
the Palestinians joining later talks on a final resolution.
   Negotiations between Egypt and Israel ended in 1981 and neither
the Palestinians nor Arab states considers the Camp David process a
viable option.
   Olmert, the Likud lawmaker, helped draft the Likud platform and
said ``there is no role for the PLO,'' which Israel considers a
terrorist group, but dovish Labor Party members appear to be
reconsidering that position.
   Burg, the Labor candidate, told Israel radio earlier this week:
``Once the PLO accepts U.N. resolutions 242 and 338, abandons the
ways of terror and recognizes the state of Israel, it won't be the
same entity. Once it is not the same entity it will make me
reconsider my attitude toward it.''
   Those resolutions guarantee Israel's right to exist within
secure borders in return for its withdrawal from occupied Arab
territory.
   The PLO has moved in recent months to modify its stance toward
Israel and, perhaps, win world support for a role in governing the
occupied lands. Bassam Abu Sharif, chief PLO spokesman, has
advocated recognizing Israel and establishing an independent
Palestinian state in the territories.
   In Israel, the future of the West Bank and Gaza Strip has become
a campaign issue.
   Benjamin Netanyahu, Israel's former U.N. ambassador and a Likud
candidate for parliament, said this week: ``The public is concerned
about the problem of staying in the territories, but it is
significantly more concerned about the vulnerability we will invite
on ourselves if we get out of the territories.''
   He said Arab control of the occupied lands might threaten Israel
by providing a ``front door'' for invasion, and such weapons as
shoulder-fired missiles could threaten all Israeli air strips.
   Netanyahu said the uprising should be ended, followed by a
``cooling-off period'' and an autonomy plan that gives Israel
maximum security and the Arab residents minimum interference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
