<DOCNO> AP880905-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 1238EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-WorldSales Bjt   09-05 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Sales, Bjt,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Government Catalogue For Discerning Customers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Better or otherwise, this mousetrap uses
neither springs nor poison. If that doesn't strike your fancy, how
about a kit for making your own four-seater plane? Could you use a
few dozen cow gallstones?
   All this and more can be found in a federal government catalogue
designed to help peddle U.S. goods around the world.
   Among the other novelties listed in the monthly publication
``Commercial News USA'' is a machine for making miniature
doughnuts. And there's genuine Kiowa Indian beef jerky.
   The Department of Commerce sends 110,000 copies every month to
U.S. missions in 140 countries, but does not distribute them in the
United States. The magazine has an index in French and Spanish as
well as English and some missions translate the entire issue.
   The Foreign Agricultural Service of the Agriculture Department
takes inquiries from other countries and makes them available
through computer information networks to Americans with farm
products to sell. Some are published in the Journal of Commerce, a
business daily in New York.
   Earlier in the 1980s, the inquiries included such exotic items
as the cow gallstones _ for use in Chinese medicine _ as well as
four-leaf clovers and turtle eggs. ``Foreign Agriculture,''
published monthly by the department, says it does not know what the
clover and turtle eggs were for.
   It quotes Stan Barrett, one of the department's marketing
specialists, as saying it now prefers to concentrate on more
mundane products like wheat, wood, beef and poultry.
   Last year, the countries with the most requests were Taiwan,
Japan, Britain, Kuwait, Oman, the United Arab Emirates, Egypt,
Bahrain, West Germany and Canada.
   Manufacturers pay $150 to get a small black-and-white photo and
a brief description of their product in ``Commercial News USA.''
   The miniature doughnut machine, called ``Lil' Orbits,'' is
considered one of the magazine's success stories. Janet Ebner, its
program director, said in an interview that its mention in the
magazine brought $600,000 worth of business for the manufacturer in
Minneapolis. He had visits from interested agents in West Germany
and Thailand, and negotiations with a Japanese distributor.
   The mousetrap works this way: The mouse crawls in to get the
bait, tips the trap and causes the door to lock behind it. It costs
42 to 50 cents wholesale and can be either reused or thrown away
with the mouse inside.
   The do-it-yourself airplane kit costs $40,000. The manufacturer
claims the resulting plane, when put together from the instructions
that come with it, has a cruising speed of 200 miles an hour, a
range of 1,000 miles and a useful load of 850 pounds.
   Beef jerky is marinated, dried meat in thin pieces about an inch
wide. The word comes from the Quechua Indians in Peru, but the
version now being exported is made by a Kiowa Indian from Oklahoma,
Robert Rowell.
   He sold a contract to Harrods department store in London after
being helped by the Foreign Agricultural Service to exhibit at a
British food show.
   ``It goes well with beer,'' said Dugger Harris, of the High
Value Products Division at the service. ``They drink a lot of beer
over there.''
   Rowell won an award from President Reagan as ``National Minority
Business Person of the Year,'' but then he got into trouble with
British health authorities who disapproved of the quality of the
Oklahoma water used to prepare the beef before it was dried.
   ``That's all right now,'' Harris said in an interview. ``Harrods
is selling it again and he's talking with the Japanese.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880905-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 1240EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DrugBill Bjt   09-05 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Bill, Bjt,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Something For Everybody, Democrats And Republicans Alike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Democratic leadership has stamped a
showcase drug-fighting bill ``bipartisan,'' and is trying to secure
GOP support by permitting votes on conservative-inspired issues
like the death penalty.
   The strategy, devised by Speaker Jim Wright of Texas, could
produce an overwhelming majority for legislation that incumbents
from both parties could use in their election races.
   Debate begins Wednesday, and a final vote could take place
Friday. The Senate will then follow with its own drug bill and the
two versions would eventually be merged into final legislation.
   The bipartisan approach could blunt any Republican plans to
paint Democrats as soft on crime _ a theme already sounded by Vice
President George Bush.
   ``I don't think being tough on drugs means Republicans,'' said
House Majority Whip Tony Coelho, D-Calif., ``Many Democrats feel
just as strongly as Republicans, because we think it's right.''
   House Republicans, on the other hand, won't have to rant and
rave as they often do that Democrats use the rules to keep GOP
proposals from House votes.
   They'll have guaranteed votes on amendments that advance their
political agenda. Many Democrats may join them in some votes. The
key issues will be a federal death penalty, denial of federal
benefits and state driver's licenses to drug users, and a ``good
faith'' exception to admit illegally seized drug evidence.
   The House bill as introduced carries a $1.5 billion to $2
billion annual pricetag, money that would be added to the $3.9
billion a year the federal government is now spending to fight drug
abuse.
   The legislation includes something for everyone involved in
fighting illegal drugs: more money for education, treatment and
rehabilitation; and more resources for state and local law
enforcement efforts to seize drugs on land, in the air and on the
seas.
   But there also are new twists, such as controlling the U.S.-made
chemicals that find their way to foreign cocaine laboratories, and
old controversies, like gun control.
   The bill contains a seven-day waiting period for handgun
purchasers that has become the latest cause for both the gun owner
and pro-regulation groups.
   Gun control organizations argue that a national waiting period
would make it more difficult for drug dealers to obtain handguns,
mainly in the 28 states that now have no waiting period. Pro-gun
organizations protest that only law-abiding citizens would be
harmed by the delay, because criminals would not go to legitimate
dealers.
   The key GOP amendments would:
   _Provide a mandatory death penalty against those who commit
murder in the course of a federal drug felony. One liberal
Democratic alternative calls for mandatory life imprisonment.
   _Allow admission in court of improperly seized drug evidence if
law enforcement officers acted in ``good faith.''
   _Deny student loans, FHA mortgages, rent subsidies and other
federal benefits to convicted drug users until they complete
rehabilitation programs. After rehabilitation, benefits would be
reinstated.
   Another GOP-sponsored amendment, which some Republicans oppose,
would require the revocation or suspension of a driver's license
for those convicted of a drug-related offense. Federal money would
be withheld from states to force compliance.
   Rep. Charles B. Rangel, D-N.Y. and chairman of the House select
committee on narcotics, said he doesn't care much for the
bipartisan approach. ``Once the leadership said `bipartisan,' the
Republicans wanted these draconian measures,'' he said.
   Rangel said that for conservatives, ``the litmus test for
commitment is the federal death penalty.'' The death penalty now is
applied only for state crimes, because Congress has not adopted the
constitutional standards required to carry out capital punishment.
   However, Coelho predicted that many Democrats would back the
death penalty and suggested the main party split would come over
the GOP plan to deny benefits to drug users.
   To address complaints from local officials who said they never
received promised anti-drug grants, the bill would require states
to automatically pass through anti-drug money to local governments.
   Banking law revisions would allow the government to closely
watch institutions where drug money might be laundered.
   Recipients of federal grants or contracts would need to maintain
a drug-free workplace.
   Money would be provided for drug education, treatment and
rehabilitation for AIDS victims and groups with a high risk of
getting the disease.
   The legislation would authorize $10 million for a Latin American
regional anti-drug force if one is approved by the Organization of
American States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
