<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Lendl-Immigration     09-05 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lendl-Immigration,435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Bid To Put Lendl On U.S. Olympic Team Fails</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional bid to grant tennis star Ivan
Lendl immediate American citizenship so he could play on the U.S.
Olympic team failed because Czechoslovakian officials refused to
provide waivers for their native son, lawmakers said.
   Lendl, the world's top-ranked tennis player, has lived in
Greenwich, Conn., since 1981 and wanted to represent his adopted
homeland in Seoul this month. ``I am very excited about the
possibilities of playing in the Olympics, Davis Cup and World Team
Cup for America,'' the tennis star said earlier this year.
   Enlisting the help of Connecticut lawmakers, Lendl won House
Judiciary Committee approval in April of a special immigration bill
that would have waived the necessary five-year waiting period and
given him immediate citizenship.
   That was a major victory because Rep. Romano L. Mazzoli, D-Ky.,
chairman of the immigration subcommittee, generally opposes
Olympic-tied immigration bills. Proponents considered the
subcommittee vote Lendl's biggest potential stumbling block.
   But on the House floor, Rep. F. James Sensenbrenner Jr., R-Wis.,
blocked the measure and said he would drop his opposition only if
the proponents could secure a guarantee from the Czech government
that it would provide a waiver for Lendl to represent the United
States in the Olympics.
   Olympic rules required a waiver because Lendl previously
represented Czechoslovakia in international competition at the
Davis Cup.
   Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., who represents Greenwich, and
Rep. Bruce A. Morrison, D-Conn., a member of the House Judiciary
Committee, urged Czech officials to grant the waiver. They refused.
   In a terse dispatch to Shays relayed through the embassy, the
Czechoslovak Association of Physical Culture wrote: ``The
Czechoslovak Olympic Committee does not have any reason to agree
with the representation of Ivan Lendl in the team of the United
States at the Olympic Games in Seoul.''
   ``We pressed the issue,'' Morrison said in a telephone interview
last week. ``Maybe we could have (succeeded) with more time, but
... time has basically run out.''
   Morrison said he, Shays and Sen. Lowell P. Weicker Jr., R-Conn.,
pushed the legislation solely in the hopes of getting Lendl on the
U.S. Olympic team. With that ruled out, legislation to give him
fast-track citizenship will be abandoned.
   Lendl, 28, received his permanent residence status last year. He
will be eligible for citizenship through traditional procedures in
1992. His attorney and spokeswoman did not return telephone calls
last week.
   Tim Mayotte and Brad Gilbert will be the U.S. men's singles
players at Seoul.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
