<DOCNO> AP880905-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 1321EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Law     09-05 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Law,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislature Approves China's First State Secret Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's legislature approved the nation's first
law to protect state secrets, a strict regulation that stipulates
life sentences and even the death penalty for violators, it was
announced Monday.
   The law was adopted Monday by the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress, which handles the day-to-day affairs of
the congress, the Xinhua News Agency said. The panel then adjourned
a weeklong meeting.
   The 35-article law protects national security and obliges all
citizens and organizations to keep state secrets. The law will go
into effect in May, replacing provisional regulations on state
secrets that were issued in 1951.
   The Xinhua dispatch defined state secrets as ``important
decisions of national defense, diplomatic affairs, secret affairs
concerning the national economic and social development and science
and technology and activities related to state safety and to the
investigation of crime.''
   The law divides state secrets into three categories: strictly
confidential, confidential and secret. Disclosure of strictly
confidential information would seriously damage state safety and
interests, it said.
   Those who steal, secretly gather, buy or illegally provide state
secrets to foreigners or foreign institutions will be sentenced to
between five and 10 years in prison for minor cases.
   In extremely serious cases, the sentence is a minimum of 10
years, life imprisonment or the death penalty, Xinhua said.
</TEXT>
