<HEAD>New Triangular $2 Coin Very Popular In Cook Islands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Cook Islands introduced the
world's first triangular $2 coin last year, it was advertised as
money from paradise.
   Apparently the campaign worked too well.
   Radio Cooks, monitored in Sydney, said Monday that investors,
mostly from New Zealand, have scooped up virtually all the 90,000
coins that were minted.
   Richard McDonald, director of the Cook Islands Numismatics
Bureau, blamed the run on the widely distributed brochures that
advertised the coin.
   The Cook Islands, population 20,000, is a self-governing
dependency of New Zealand. The coral islands in the South Pacific
lie nearly 1,900 miles northeast of Auckland, New Zealand.
