<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AshlandLawsuit     09-05 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ashland Lawsuit,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Ashland Executive Undecided On How To Use New Wealth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHLAND, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Ashland Oil executive who won a
$16.7 million settlement after charging he was wrongfully fired for
refusing to offer bribes to foreign officials says he has not
decided how to use his wealth.
   The majority of the settlement _ the $12.25 million former
Ashland vice president Bill E. McKay Jr. was awarded for being
wrongfully discharged _ is tax-free.
   He and fellow former vice president Harry Williams filed suit
claiming they were illegally fired for refusing to offer bribes to
foreign officials or to cover up such bribes.
   An eight-week jury trial of their case in Covington ended June
10 with a $69.5 million decision against Ashland, and a finding
that Ashland violated the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt
Organizations Act by engaging in a pattern of illegal interstate
activity to obtain oil in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
   Ashland later sought a new trial or a different judgment, and
finally agreed to pay the two men $25 million.
   As part of the settlement, McKay, Williams and the court agreed
to set aside the RICO finding.
   McKay said last week he was still trying to recover from the
stress of intense negotiations that led up to the settlement.
   Among the settlement's numerous terms is one providing that
McKay and Williams cannot portray themselves in any future movie
versions of the case. ``That (point) wasn't hard to give up,''
McKay said.
   After the trial, McKay had said that his expenses were enormous
and that he had been unable to find employment equal to his
six-figure position at Ashland Oil.
   He is paid $50,000 a year as a consultant to Englehard Corp., a
New Jersey company which supplies catalysts to refineries, and he
hopes to land other consulting contracts.
   Williams has moved to Boca Raton, Fla.
   In addition to his share of the $25 million, McKay and his
attorneys received a taxable $2 million for breach of contract.
They also won almost $2.5 million for various expenses; the
agreement did not make clear whether that money was taxable.
   Ashland Oil's $25 million settlement was paid Aug. 26.
   The settlement agreement also gave McKay and his attorneys $1.65
million for expenses related to the case.
   McKay said last week that money did not cover legal fees but was
for related costs such as depositions, copying documents and hotel
bills.
   McKay and Tachau declined to discuss details not included in the
written agreement, such as the attorneys' percentage of the
settlement.
   Tachau's law firm _ Brown, Todd & Heyburn _ had as many as nine
attorneys and several staff members working on McKay's case, Tachau
said. The firm also opened a temporary office in Covington during
the eight-week trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880905-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 1330EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Airline'sDemise     09-05 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airline's Demise,0723</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Provincetown-Boston, Nation's Oldest Commuter Airline, Officially
Dies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Provincetown-Boston Airlines, the nation's first
regional commuter carrier and once the largest, officially dies
Tuesday.
   In reality, it died four years ago.
   ``What's happening now is like watching a patient catching
cancer,'' said John C. Van Arsdale Jr., who had to resign as PBA's
chairman after the Federal Aviation Administration stripped his
pilot's license in disastrous 1984. ``When the patient dies, it's
merciful.''
   Some industry analysts say the demise of the 39-year-old airline
is an example of how deregulation has crippled small commuter
airlines, partly by spurring fare wars and unchecked growth.
   John Van Arsdale Sr. started the carrier on Nov. 30, 1949, with
just a two-seat Cessna 140.
   Over the years, PBA routinely ran extra planes to Cape Cod and
area resort islands if more passengers showed up, and it grew in
the early 1980s after Van Arsdale turned control over to his
expansion-minded sons.
   Then came back-to-back fatal accidents in 1984. The federal
government shut down the airline because of safety and training
violations. Two weeks after it was flying again, 13 people died in
a crash in Florida. Bankruptcy and takeover followed close behind.
   The bitter Van Arsdale sons say the FAA overreacted to minor
problems. The father says his sons too brashly expanded what was a
cozy and profitable regional service.
   ``We didn't overreact at all,'' said FAA spokesman Jack Barker.
``We reacted properly and in the interest of aviation safety.''
   PBA formally ceases to be an airline Tuesday when its parent,
Bar Harbor Airways of Bangor, Maine, a tiny part of the giant Texas
Air Corp., retires its federal operating certificate.
   PBA's planes are being sold _ including N136PB, a DC-3 flying
since the durable breed went out of production in the 1940s _ and
service on some routes will be reduced or canceled, Bar Harbor
sales director Steven Mason said.
   ``You might lay the whole thing at the door of deregulation,''
said Jon Hurdle, associate editor of Travel Weekly, who has written
about PBA. ``Van Arsdale Jr. was worried about the competitive
effects of deregulation, so he expanded arguably more than he
should have.''
   Over the years, Van Arsdale conservatively expanded service. In
the late 1950s, he worked out a innovative deal with Naples
Airlines in Florida under which the two carriers borrowed each
other's services in the off-season; Naples sent its planes and
crews north in the summer, while PBA's operations migrated south in
winter.
   Then he retired in 1980, turning PBA over to his sons, Peter and
John Jr., who bought more planes, acquired another small airline
and bulked up operations. Flights were added around New England and
the South.
   ``I had reservations,'' said the elder Van Arsdale, 68. ``I felt
they were moving a little too fast. On the other hand, everything
seemed to be going well.''
   By 1983, PBA was the largest regional commuter in the nation. It
carried 220,000 passengers in 1979 and saw its load grow six times
to 1.3 million in the first nine months of 1984, a period in which
PBA reported profits of $3.3 million on revenues of $58.4 million.
   By the end of 1984, PBA had 1,600 employees, 500 daily flights
and 104 planes.
   ``In order to survive in a deregulated environment we had to
grow,'' said John Jr., 43.
   ``They were the envy of some carriers for some time because they
made money,'' said George James, president of Airlines Economics
Inc., a Washington-based aviation consultant.
   Then came the crashes and the FAA scrutiny.
   Public confidence collapsed. Passenger traffic dropped 50
percent in two days, bankers tightened the reins on more than $30
million in credit, the stock plummeted.
   PBA filed for bankruptcy in March 1985. A year later it was
bought for $30 million by People Express, itself now defunct.
   Alfred Kahn, a Cornell University economics professor who headed
the now-defunct Civil Aeronautics Board when it deregulated the
industry in 1978, disagrees that deregulation is to blame for PBA's
collapse.
   ``Deregulation gave people an opportunity to make money, as some
of them have,'' he said, ``and gave other people a chance to make
mistakes.''
</TEXT>
