<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JewishTV     09-05 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jewish TV,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Seeks To Establish First Jewish TV Station </HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group wants to start what it believes
would be the first television station in the country that offers a
full slate of programming aimed at a Jewish audience.
   Bridgeways Communications of Westport said its programming would
be cultural rather than religious.
   ``It will not be the Jewish version of the 700 Club,'' said
Michael Vlock, Bridgeways' president.
   The station's target audience would be the 3 million Jews living
in northern New Jersey, metropolitan New York, and Connecticut.
   ``The station is intended to be both a resource and a
celebration of the contributions the Jewish community has made to
society,'' Vlock said.
   While the programs would be designed to appeal to Jews, ``we
want to be attractive to a broader audience as well,'' Vlock said.
   The station plans to offer programming in areas such as the
arts, education, travel, politics, science, history, business and
current events, Vlock said.
   Bridgeways now operates WBCT-TV, Channel 43, a home shopping
channel, which he said was started to preserve the company's FCC
license before becoming a station offering Jewish programming.
   Investors have already raised and spent $3 million to finance
construction of the station's transmitter and antenna, located in
Seymour. An additional $500,000 was just raised to finance
development of the new format.
   Vlock placed the total costs of establishing the station at
about $10 million.
   If Bridgeways is to be successful in its endeavor, industry
experts say it will have to persuade cable companies in the region
to carry the station and convince advertisers that Jews will watch
its programs.
   Vlock and his mother, Laurel Vlock, chairwoman of Bridgeways,
are confident that cable networks will make room for Channel 43.
   ``People are very concerned about their roots. It's a trend in
America in all ethnicities today,'' Laurel Vlock said.
   Said Michael Vlock: ``We offer a large, focused, loyal and
well-educated audience ... what more does an advertiser want.''
</TEXT>
