<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     09-05 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country singer Randy Travis says that
when he was a teen-ager, singing in front of an audience didn't
bother him, but that was all he could do on stage.
   ``To sing was no problem, but talking scared me to death,'' said
Travis, a former short-order cook who got his start in clubs in his
native North Carolina.
   ``I didn't know what to say. Finally I worked in to saying
`Thank you,' then from there to introducing the song,'' he said.
   He's gotten more comfortable since he hit the country charts in
1986, but says he had another bout of nervousness recently when he
performed in London before rock star Mick Jagger and his girlfriend
Jerry Hall.
   ``You know in his case, he's going to hear every little mistake.
But the show went great and he and Jerry came backstage
afterwards,'' said Travis, 29.
   ``To start with he was a little stand-offish. I guess you'd say
he didn't really know what to say, or didn't want to say anything,
but once we started talking he was very friendly.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fans paid scalpers many times the
normal price for tickets to a single concert by Luciano Pavarotti,
then gave the Italian tenor a 30-minute standing ovation.
   Tickets for Sunday's concert at a 9,000-seat stadium were sold
out a few hours after going on sale last December at prices ranging
from $11 to $65. On Sunday, seats fetched up to $335 outside the
concert.
   Pavarotti sang seventeen songs, including opera arias and
lighter pieces, culminating with an encore of ``O Sole Mio.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Lawrence M. Jenco, who was held
hostage for 19 months in Lebanon, says he will move to Los Angeles
to join the staff of a Catholic student center at the University of
Southern California.
   Jenco has lived since February at The Grotto, a Marian shrine in
Portland.
   The Roman Catholic Servite priest had been director of the
Beirut operations of Catholic Relief Services for three months when
he was taken hostage by Shiite Moslem guerrillas on Jan. 8, 1985.
His release 19 months later was part of what later was revealed to
have been an arms-for-hostages swap.
   Jenco, 53, said Friday that his move is part of the regular
reassignments in his Roman Catholic religious order. He will join
the pastoral staff of the Newman Center on the USC campus.
   Jenco, who was assigned to Portland in part to provide him a
period of rest after his ordeal, said he accepted the assignment
because he enjoys the challenges of working with college youth and
because of the other challenges in Los Angeles, such as the
homeless.
   ``There are so many things to do,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former astronaut Edwin ``Buzz'' Aldrin, the second
man to walk on the moon, says he regrets the United States has
fallen behind in the space race and believes Britain should be
doing more in space.
   ``I think it's pretty clear that we have let lapse the space
technology that we had built up,'' Aldrin, now a science
consultant, told a reporter at the Farnborough Air Show.
   ``We must continue to push ahead with the space program ... The
British government must back space exploration,'' said Aldrin, 58.
   Britain is spending $200 million on space research over the next
four years, which a House of Lords select committee said was little
more than half of what was needed.
</TEXT>
