<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Quayle-TribunePoll     09-05 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle-Tribune Poll,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tribune Poll: Press Unfair to Quayle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty-two percent of likely voters in five key
states surveyed for the Chicago Tribune said they felt Dan Quayle
has not been treated fairly by the press, the paper reported Monday.
   But nearly half those polled also said they felt the Indiana
senator tapped by George Bush as a running mate lacks the maturity
and experience to be president.
   The survey was conducted by Peter D. Hart Research Associates of
Washington for the Chicago Tribune. Hart, who was Walter Mondale's
pollster in 1984, surveyed 1,509 people in Illinois, California,
Florida, New York and Texas in late August.
   Asked for their views on the statement, ``Dan Quayle does not
have the maturity and experience to be vice president,'' 47 percent
agreed, 39 percent disagreed and 14 percent were unsure.
   But 62 percent of those answering agreed that ``the press has
not treated Dan Quayle fairly,'' the Tribune said. Twenty-eight
percent disagreed with that statement.
   The media grilled Quayle after his nomination about whether his
wealthy family pulled strings to get him into the Indiana National
Guard at the height of the Vietnam war.
   Quayle has said he used no influence and is proud of his service
in the National Guard.
   Thirty-nine percent of those polled said they regarded Bush's
choice of Quayle as a ``negative,'' 31 percent said it was
``positive,'' and the rest had no opinion.
   Six percent of those surveyed were Vietnam-era veterans. Among
them, the choice of Quayle was viewed as positive by 22 percent and
negative by 49 percent.
   The poll indicated that Democratic vice presidential nominee
Lloyd Bentsen was viewed positively by 41 percent of all
respondents, and negatively by 23 percent.
   The margin of error for questions asked all respondents was 3.5
percentage points, and 6 points for the Vietnam-era veterans.
</TEXT>
