<HEAD>Theater Vandalized Over `Last Temptation'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vandals slashed seats at the Cineplex Odeon
Showcase Theater and spray-painted threats against a studio
executive early Monday in an apparent protest of the film ``The
Last Temptation of Christ,'' police said.
   The vandals caused an estimated $5,000 in damage to the Showcase
Theater. The theater isn't showing the film but it is part of the
Cineplex Odeon chain, which is showing the movie in Century City.
   The painted threats were aimed at Lew Wasserman, chairman of MCA
Inc., parent company of Universal Studios, which produced the film.
   One message written below the screen said: ``Lew Wasserman: If
you release `The Last Temptation of Christ,' we will wait years and
decimate all Universal property. This message is for your insurance
company.''
   The movie has angered fundamentalist Christians because it
depicts a Christ who doubts his divinity and is susceptible to
human temptation.
