<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 1634EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burma     09-05 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Issue Ultimatum To Burmese Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students threatened on Monday to launch
further strikes and mass protests unless an interim government is
formed to supervise multiparty elections that would end 26 years of
one-party rule.
   In another development, at least 20 people were killed in a
Rangoon suburb in a clash between neighborhood security patrols and
thieves.
   The Students Action Supervision Committee told reporters the
government must meet their demands by 8 p.m. Wednesday or protests
will follow Thursday.
   Opponents of the Burma Socialist Program Party have rejected
President Maung Maung's proposed nationwide referendum on the
future of his party.
   For the past weeks, the government has been crippled by strikes
and daily demonstrations, and a Western diplomat estimated that 40
town administrations were taken over by protesters. Neighborhood
committees, formed largely of students and Buddhist monks, have
patrolled many areas of the country against the spreading
lawlessness and violence.
   On Sunday, residents of the Rangoon suburb of South Okkalapa
said a bloody clash occurred after thieves captured 15 members of a
neighborhood committee who rushed to a government biscuit factory
to stop looting.
   On Monday, a mob burst into the factory, where they found eight
members of the committee dead, including two monks. The mob then
killed 12 thieves, captured 10 and set fire to nearby houses
belonging to people suspected of involvement in the looting, the
residents said. The thieves reportedly included people recently
released from jail.
   More than 10,000 prisoners have been released or escaped from
Burma jails over the past two weeks in what some diplomats
speculate was a calculated move by the government to create chaos
to justify a military crackdown.
   The All Burma Students Union on Monday released what it said was
a secret Aug. 22 directive from the head of government military
intelligence.
   ``Under prevailing conditions in the country, intelligence units
and their informers must use various methods to cause fear and
confusion among the public,'' the directive said. It bore a
signature and official stamp, but its authenticity could not be
verified.
   A Japanese Burma scholar, Minoru Kiryu, said on Monday the
situation in the country was ``chaotic'' and it was uncertain if
Maung Maung's government would survive until the party meeting.
   Also Monday, more than 50,000 people held a solemn ceremony on a
lake in suburban Rangoon for student protesters said to have been
killed, assaulted and drowned there by police during March 17
anti-government demonstrations.
   Wreaths were placed on a flower-decked raft which drifted away
as many students wept and prayed aloud.
   The government said at least 43 people died in the March riots,
but Western diplomats said at least 100 people were killed.
   Demonstrations flared in June and again after ruler Ne Win
resigned July 23 after 26 years in power. The party chose
hard-liner Sein Lwin to succeed him.
   Government radio said 112 people died in Rangoon in rioting
against Sein Lwin, who resigned after only 17 days in power.
Diplomats believe many more people were killed.
   Maung Maung took power Aug. 19 as the first civilian leader in
26 years.
</TEXT>
