<HEAD>Secret Service Arrest Man In Connection With Bush Rally Incident</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS grafs 5-7, bgng, Steve Sergek xxx etc., to UPDATE
with Secret Service statement.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO, (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secret Service agents Monday arrested a man
they said was carrying an electric stun gun during a campaign
appearance by Vice President George Bush, a Bush spokeswoman said.
   The unidentified man, who allegedly had a so-called Tazer gun
strapped onto the outside of his camera bag, was being held by San
Diego police, said spokeswoman Sheila Tate.
   The incident happened as Bush was shaking hands with a Labor Day
crowd after he gave a speech to a group of employees of a
fish-processing plant on the San Diego waterfront.
   The man was arrested ``after being spotted by one of the
agents,'' Ms. Tate said. ``He is now in custody.''
   Steve Sergek, the special agent in charge of the San Diego field
office of the U.S. Secret Service, said later, however, that while
the unidentified 31-year-old man had ``exercised very poor
judgment,'' the man was being released.
   ``Right now it appears there was no danger involved to the vice
president,'' Sergek said. ``The person did nothing to present a
harm to either the vice president or anyone else there.''
   Ms. Tate had said the gun was ``potentially lethal.''
   ``The vice president's reaction was, `what a great job the
agents did,''' she said.
   She said the vice president was informed of the arrest aboard
Air Force Two en route to his next campaign event in Los Angeles.
   She said further details were sketchy. She said that another
man, and possibly a third, may have been initially held, as well,
but were released.
   She said the man was arrested along a ropeline separating the
secure area where the vice president was and the public area.
