<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NavyDeath     09-05 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Death,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opening Statements Set for Tuesday in Sailor's Court-Martial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opening statements are set Tuesday for
the court-martial of a Navy rescue-swimmer instructor charged in
the drowning of a trainee.
   A five-officer panel will hear the case of Petty Officer Michael
W. Combe, 28, of Tempe, Ariz. He is charged with involuntary
manslaughter, battery and conspiracy to commit battery in the March
2 death of Airman Recruit Lee Mirecki, 19, of Appleton, Wis.
   His trial has been delayed a full week by extended pretrial
motions in his case and the court-martial of his former boss, Lt.
Thomas A. Torchia, 32, of Princeton, Ill.
   A four-member court-martial last week found Torchia, former
officer in charge of the Navy Rescue Swimmer School, innocent of
dereliction of duty in Mirecki's death.
   Much of the prosecution testimony in Combe's trial is expected
to mirror that in Torchia's case.
   In the earlier court-martial, a pathologist testified that
Mirecki, who had a phobia about being dragged under water, drowned
in a swimming pool at Pensacola Naval Air Station after suffering a
fear-induced heart attack.
   Combe is accused of holding his head under after instructors
threw the panic-striken victim back into the pool when he climbed
out and tried to exercise his right to drop out of the voluntary
training, witnesses testified.
   Torchia, who was on the telephone in his office overlooking the
pool, blamed the instructors for exceeding their authority and
using bad judgment. He testified that if he had been present
Mirecki would still be alive, but he saw and heard nothing to alert
him the recruit was in danger.
   The prosecution and defense each plan to call as many as 30
witnesses in Combe's case, expected to take at least through the
end of the week.
   Listed as defense witnesses are four instructors already
punished for forcing Mirecki back into the pool. None of them had
testified in Torchia's trial.
   Neither Torchia nor his former boss, now-retired Navy Capt. C.L.
Lavinder, who received a reprimand for dereliction of duty, are
listed as potential witnesses by the defense or the prosecution.
</TEXT>
