<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 1716EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-River     09-05 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-River,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Worst Of Drought Is Over For Mississippi River, But Problems
Linger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shipping companies, the Coast Guard and the
Army Corps of Engineers are joining in an unprecedented effort to
ensure that the drought-caused bottlenecks that idled Mississippi
River traffic this summer won't recur, a shipping industry
executive says.
   The three groups are forming a task force and establishing a
clearinghouse at Cincinnait to share information about the
Mississippi and Ohio Rivers, according to Jeffrey Smith, vice
president of a shipping industry group called American Waterway
Operators.
   The drought, Smith said, has cost the industry an estimated $200
million, about 20 percent of its annual operating revenue.
   However, the worst of the 1988 drought may be past for those who
work on or live along the river, some officials believe.
   An underwater dike built by the Corps, for example, has stopped
saltwater from creeping up the Mississippi and fouling the water
supply for New Orleans. However, the Corps has had to supply by
barge some downriver communities with millions of gallons of fresh
water.
   At New Orleans, the river is running at a rate of about 130,000
cubic feet per second _ about 55 percent of normal for this time of
year. In early July, however, it was closer to 114,000.
   ``We're still way below average,'' said Roger Steakely, a Corps
spokesman in Vicksburg, Miss. ``But we're not nearly as bad as we
were.''
   Gulf of Mexico waters have pushed their way up the
drought-reduced river, turning the muddy, brown water a beautiful
blue-green and threatening the water supply for New Orleans, which
is about 100 miles from the mouth of the Mississippi.
   Because the salty water is heavier than the fresh Mississippi
water, the Corps decided to impede the flow by building a dirt dam
15 to 25 feet high across the river bottom.
   The $790,000 structure, about 30 miles south of New Orleans,
succeeded in heading off the salty flow. It was too late, however,
for some small communities in Plaquemines Parish, where the Corps
continues to deliver barge-loads of water from farther upriver.
   By the middle of last week, the Corps had barged 52 million
gallons for those communities, according to Bruce Sossaman, a
spokesman for the New Orleans office of the Corps.
   The increased flow on the Mississippi also means a reduction in
the number of bottlenecks that idled traffic upriver in June. Last
week, the Coast Guard relaxed restrictions on towboat loads that
had been imposed earlier this summer because of low water levels on
the lower Mississippi.
   The task of the clearinghouse on river conditions is to ensure
that everyone on the river is informed of current developments,
Smith said.
   ``It's a matter of the industry and the Coast Guard and the
Corps working smarter,'' said Smith. ``They took all the
communications that were disparate and decentralized, and
centralized them out of one office on the Ohio River.''
   As for how long the drought will affect the rivers, the experts
aren't sure.
   ``Based on what the weather service has said, there's virtually
no way we're going to get back to normal ... We've been hearing
we're in for drought conditions on the river through the remainder
of the summer,'' said Sossaman.
   The amount of rain needed to bring the river back up to its
average flow rate may not come around until next spring, Steakely
said. And that's all right with him.
   A sudden heavy flow of water down the Mississippi would dump
more sand and sediment down river and could cause as many problems
with navigation as it would solve, Steakely said.
   Slow, steady improvement is better, he said. ``We really aren't
hoping for a dramatic change quickly.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
