<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     09-05 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITEHALL, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twisted Sister and Motley Crue may not
know it, but their music is keeping ducks and geese alive in
western Montana.
   The migrating waterfowl hate the heavy-metal rock music by the
groups so much that they avoid a pond contaminated by cyanide where
the music is kept playing on loudspeakers 24 hours a day.
   The contaminated pond is at the Golden Sunlight Mine near
Whitehall, where cyanide is used to leach gold from ore. The
cyanide flows into a 250-acre settling pond, where it is poisonous
to waterfowl.
   Don Jenkins, the mine's administrative superintendent, read how
rock music was used to scare starlings from a New York airport. He
decided to try Twisted Sister, Motley Crue, Scorpions and others.
   He also uses propane-powered cannons that fire every couple of
minutes, and security guards who occasionally fire shotgun blasts
or flare guns. Colored helium balloons bob up and down.
   But, says Jenkins, ``the rock music is still the best ploy we've
got.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All the trustees of a private elementary school
wanted was a new gymnasium, a library and room for more offices.
   What Trinity School got was more like a castle.
   ``Kindergothic'' is the word coined by architects Terry Sargent
and Larry Lord to describe an architectural style that combines a
crystal-studded rock wall and turret rising from a ravine. The
front entrance is sheltered by skewed columns of stacked stone
cubes.
   ``It's architecture for children without being ridiculous,''
Sargent said. ``We used details in an informal way so children
could look at it and actually learn something about architecture.''
   Passersby are startled but children are delighted.
   ``There's a whimsical quality about the new structures that at
first rocks the adult back a little bit, but the children ... see
it as they might imagine a castle would be like ... (filled with)
all kinds of strange windows and beautifully colored objects,''
said Chuck Johnston, headmaster at Trinity throughout the project.
</TEXT>
