<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0581,0861</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kurds Claim 7,000 Iraqi Casualties; Iraq Denies It</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-13 UPDATE with Vincennes departure postponed,
U.N. observer comment, other. PICKS up 9th graf pvs, According to .
.. with minor editing to TRIM.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kurdish guerrillas claimed Monday they
killed or wounded 7,000 Iraqi soldiers who they said attacked their
mountain strongholds in northern Iraq with chemical weapons.
   The guerrillas also said 1,900 civilians died and some bases
were lost.
   Iraq denied the claims.
   In Baghdad, Iraqi authorities displayed thousands of Iranian
weapons they said were captured in offensives before a cease-fire
took effect Aug. 20 in the 8-year-old war with Iran.
   Also on Monday:
   _Iran accused Iraq of violating the cease-fire by bombing
villages in northwestern Iran with fighter-bombers. Iraq denied it.
   _The head of the U.N. observers, Gen. Slovko Jovic, said after a
visit to the southern front that ``there are some minor problems
that we are trying to resolve. Many of the problems we have been
able to solve.'' He did not detail the problems. He spoke in an
Iranian TV interview, monitored in Nicosia.
   _U.S. officials abruptly postponed for at least five days the
scheduled pullout of the missile cruiser Vincennes from the Persian
Gulf region after at least one Arab government raised last-minute
objections, U.S. military sources said. The vessel was to have
ended its patrol duties with the U.S. Joint Task Force Middle East
on Sunday and was earlier reported to actually have left.
   One source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the change
of orders for the Vincennes was based on ``diplomatic rather than
military'' considerations, and ``came from a much higher level''
than the Navy in the gulf. He said a previously announced Pentagon
decision not to replace the cruiser still stood.
   _In Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, the foreign ministers of the Arab gulf
states urged the five permanent members of the U.N. Security
Council to help push along the peace talks between Iraq and Iran
that began Aug. 25 in Geneva.
   The five permanent members are the United States, the Soviet
Union, China, Britain and France.
   U.N. mediator Jan Eliasson spent more than two hours Monday in
Geneva with Iranian officials, seeking a solution to the deadlock
in negotiations on an end to the war, which has cost up to 1
million lives and hundreds of billions of dollars.
   There was no word of progress on the 12th day of the
negotiations. U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar has
been serving as mediator, but left Geneva on Thursday for other
business and chose Eliasson to continue the work.
   Iraqi newspapers accused Iran of stalling the talks and Sadoun
Hamadi, a high Foreign Ministry official, left for the United
States. The official news agency said he would meet with Secretary
of State George P. Shultz.
   According to the Kurdish guerrillas, most of the civilians were
killed in 65 villages they say have been attacked with chemicals.
   ``Most of the Kurdish civilian casualties are from constant
Iraqi poison gas attacks on their villages and settlements,'' a
spokesman for the Kurdish Democratic Party told The Associated
Press in a telephone interview.
   Baghdad's official Iraqi news agency said Iraq ``strongly denied
fabricated allegations reported by The Associated Press on the use
of chemical weapons in north Iraq.''
   It quoted a commentator, not identified, as saying: ``These
figures are only present in the figments of imagination of those
who wove them'' and declared:
   ``All that happened in the north of Iraq was that a group of
traitors of Iran's agents collapsed and those of them who fled
abroad could not find but lies to cover up their defeat.''
   The agency said President Saddam Hussein's government was
preparing to ``sue newspapers involved in publishing false reports
on alleged use of chemical weapons in the north of Iraq.''
   Iran said Monday that 5,000 Iraqi Kurds fleeing chemical attacks
had arrived on its territory.
   A dispatch from the official Islamic Republic News Agency quoted
Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashami as saying 2,000 of the Kurds
had arrived via Turkey. It quoted Mohtashami as condemning the
United Nations, human rights groups and the media for not speaking
out.
   An estimated 70,000 to 90,000 Iraq Kurds fled to Turkey in the
past week, but Turkish officials said Monday the influx had stopped
because Iraqi soldiers had blocked mountain passes leading to the
border.
   Turkey's foreign minister, Mesut Yilmaz, told reporters: ``The
way Iraqi forces are deployed, actual crossing has become
impossible.''
   In Syria, an enemy of Iraq and Iran's ally in the war, the
official news agency said President Hafez Assad met with Jalal
Talbani, a Kurdish guerrilla leader. No details were given.
   Iraq displayed hundreds of captured Iranian tanks and artillery
pieces to underline its claim that Iran suffered devastating losses
in battles just before the truce began.
   Brig. Muthanna Nasiri stood before an array of weaponry that
stretched in deep ranks for more than a mile on the outskirts of
Baghdad.
</TEXT>
