<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BuffaloRoam     09-05 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Buffalo Roam,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Renegade Buffalo Corraled In Roundup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve of 14 renegade buffalo were rounded up on a
south Florida range _ bordering Interstate 75 and Florida's
Turnpike _ by latter-day trailhands on all-terrain motorcycles.
   The two bison still at large, a female calf and a bull, are the
last of 250 that escaped in March from a livestock ranch near Miami
when horse rustlers cut through a fence, said Dr. Arnold Oper,
their owner.
   The roundup didn't come off without incident. A 30-year-old
television reporter, Albert ``Bud'' Fraga, tumbled seven feet onto
his head from a swamp buggy, and was reported in serious condition
Monday with a broken sternum and two cracked vertebrae.
   The roundup of the buffalo, also known as bison, began at dawn
Sunday in 240 acres of marsh and pasture land near the border of
Dade and Broward counties.
   Oper, 64, risked jail for himself and confiscation of his
animals if he did not round up the renegades this weekend,
according to officials with the Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish
Commission. He had made several efforts to capture the animals.
   Since the breakout, the 800- to 900-pound animals have
frightened golfers at the Hollywood Lakes Country Club in Pembroke
Pines and startled motorists on I-75 and Florida's Turnpike.
   On Aug. 16, a Florida Highway Patrol dispatcher hit one of the
buffalo while driving on the interstate, killing the animal and
demolishing her car.
   About 35 volunteers on seven all-terrain motorcycles and four
swamp buggies drove the buffalo herd west through scrub myrtle and
Florida holly and into a camouflaged pen where they were coaxed
back into a cattle trailer for a trip back to the livestock ranch.
</TEXT>
