<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-05 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most Of Nation Has Nice Weather For Labor Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain was scattered over the South and sections of the Northeast
on Monday but most of the rest of the nation had sunshine for Labor
Day.
   Rain and scattered thunderstorms extended across central and
southern Florida and along coastal sections of Georgia and the
Carolinas.
   Many locations in northern Florida received around an inch of
rain during the morning. Heavier rainfall during the six hours up
to 2 p.m. EDT included 1.51 inches at Gainesville, Fla.
   Jacksonville, Fla., had gotten over 5 inches already this month
and more rain was expected Tuesday.
   By contrast, the drought in the northern Rockies has meant 13
months in a row of below-normal precipitation at Havre, Mont.,
which has not seen any measurable rain for 61 days. That is the
longest such dry period in 110 years of record keeping.
   Showers were widely scattered across the Northeast, especially
over western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia and eastern Ohio.
   Mild temperatures in the 60s, 70s and 80s prevailed across most
of the eastern half of the nation.
   Temperatures at lower elevations of the Rockies were mostly in
the 80s, and readings in the Pacific Northwest were generally in
the 60s and 70s.
   But hot weather continued over California and the desert
Southwest. Temperatures soared to over 100 by midday in sections of
the Los Angeles area. San Diego broke its record for this date of
91 degrees before noon, its third consecutive day of records.
   In the Southeast, Miami tied its record of 93 degrees.
   In the Pacific, hurricane Uleki continued to move away from
Hawaii and was no longer a significant threat to the island state.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 48
degrees at Marquette, Mich., and Saranac Lake, N.Y., to 106 at
Redding and the Alameda Naval Air Station, Calif. Sunday morning's
low was 31 degrees at Gunnison and Estes Park, Colo., and Havre,
Mont.
   For Tuesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
along a stationary front from eastern sections of the Carolinas to
northern and central Florida. Widely scattered showers were
forecast over northern New England and northeastern New York.
   Highs only in the 60s were predicted over New England, the upper
Ohio Valley and the Great Lakes region; mostly in the 70s or 80s
over the rest of the eastern half of the nation; mostly in the 80s
and 90s across the western half of the nation, but holding in the
70s in the Pacific Northwest and along the northern California
coast; and above 100 in the desert Southwest and interior valleys
of California.
</TEXT>
