<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-SeaPower     09-05 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Sea Power,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Marshal Says US Seeks Military Superiority at Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet military chief of staff said Monday the
United States has begun an arms race at sea that increases the risk
of war, and refuses to negotiate a reduction in naval forces.
   ``U.S. naval forces are a key instrument of pressure, helping to
conduct (the) U.S. positions of strength policy,'' Marshal Sergei
F. Akhromeyev wrote in a lengthy article in the Communist Party
daily Pravda.
   The article, which included Soviet statistics comparing the
superpower naval forces, appeared at a time when Western observers
say they have detected a scaling back of Soviet navy activities.
   Akhromeyev, who toured U.S. naval facilities during a visit to
the United States this summer, accused the United States and some
of its NATO allies of starting ``an arms race at sea.''
   ``They have enormous power,'' he wrote. ``The U.S. Navy
comprises 15 attack aircraft carriers, of which five are
nuclear-powered.''
   The main thrust of Akhromeyev's article was that U.S. naval
forces are designed for offensive strikes while Soviet warships are
intended to defend their country's coastline and cannot be
considered a military threat.
   As examples of the U.S. Navy's ability to deal powerful
offensive blows, Akhromeyev cited U.S. actions against Libya,
Lebanon and Grenada.
   ``In the Persian Gulf area, the United States and its allies
have amassed an armada of over 60 combatant ships, of which over
half are American,'' the Soviet chief of staff wrote.
   ``This dangerous demonstration of naval might is explained
ostensibly by the eagerness to ensure the freedom of shipping in
the Persian Gulf. The true objective is to shore up the presence of
the U.S. naval fleet on a permanent basis there.''
   He accused the United States of opposing negotiations on
reduction of naval forces or any agreement curbing their activity.
   Akhromeyev said Soviet-led Warsaw Pact countries ``do everything
depending on them to turn the world ocean from a zone of war danger
into a zone of peace and cooperation. We call upon the United
States and its NATO allies to support us in this undertaking.''
</TEXT>
