<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SeattleBlackout 1stLd-Writethru a0594 09-05 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seattle Blackout, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0594,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>50-Block Power Outage Ends in Downtown Seattle</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 9-11 `The cause ... or so.'' with 8 grafs to
UDPATE with comments on cause. Picks up 12th graf pvs `Some
customers...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Utility crews worked Monday to complete repairs
to the last of six electricity cables damaged in a fire that
blacked out 50 blocks of downtown Seattle for nearly four days.
   Workers had restored power by Sunday evening to the entire area
with the exception of one building _ a parking garage with some
office space _ near the underground vault where the fire began.
   In addition, said Seattle City Light spokesman Scott Forslund,
electricity had not been turned back on in a few buildings whose
owners weren't available or chose to wait, Forslund said.
   The sixth and final 13,000-volt cable gives the system redundant
capacity, in case of extra-heavy demand or the need to turn off
power in one of the other cables to make repairs, said Scott
Forslund, Seattle City Light spokesman.
   About half the affected customers had begun getting power when
the switch was thrown on four feeder cables Saturday evening, and
other customers were hooked up overnight before the fifth cable was
repaired Sunday evening.
   As power was restored, fire crews roamed the area to ensure that
no fires broke out in equipment on which power switches were on
when the outage began.
   City Light officials had no estimate of costs to restore power
or repair damage, City Light spokesman Hugh McIntosh said.
   The cause of the fire that sparked Seattle's biggest-ever power
outage Wednesday remained unknown, but officials said an aluminum,
direct-current supply cable for overhead electrical trolley bus
lines was a key factor in the blackout's severity.
   City Light assistant superintendent Jerry Garman said Monday
that the fire ``undoubtedly'' started in low-voltage City Light
cables, which run from transformers to feed individual buildings.
   As the system heated, power to the high-voltage feeder cables
should have been cut by ``current limiters.'' But the Metro transit
cable melted, and molten aluminum cut the high-voltage cables
before power could be cut to all but two of them.
   ``Once the DC (Metro cable) started to go ... it took what would
have been a minor inconvenience and turned it into a major event,''
Garman said.
   ``It's like we had eight or nine welding torches going at the
same time.''
   What caused the low-voltage cables to catch fire in the first
place won't be known until data is analyzed, Garman said, adding he
could not predict how long that would take.
   In the meantime, City Light crews will check other locations
with similar dual arrangements of City Light and Metro cables to
try to head off other problems, Garman said.
   ``I'm sure we're going to be looking at ways of protecting us
from them and them from us,'' he said.
   Some customers in the blacked-out area already have filed
monetary claims against the city, claiming losses as the result of
the failure, Forslund said.
   During the height of the blackout, city officials estimated that
90 percent of all businesses were closed in the area, which
included an estimated 130 restaurants, 55 shops in the popular Pike
Place Market, the Bon Marche department store, the 875-room Westin
Hotel, and uncounted other hotels, grocery stores and taverns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880905-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 1821EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfricanTalks     09-05 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South African Talks,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peace Talks to Resume Wednesday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S.-mediated peace talks
among South Africa, Angola and Cuba will reconvene Wednesday in
Brazzaville, Congo, the Department of Foreign Affairs announced.
   It said in a statement Monday that the talks were expected to
focus on the withdrawal of Cuban troops from Marxist-ruled Angola.
   Angolan rebel leader Jonas Savimbi said Saturday that Cuba has
increased its troop strength in Angola from 50,000 military
personnel to 60,000.
   Angola, Cuba and white-dominated South Africa signed a
cease-fire pact on Aug. 8 that links withdrawal of South African
and Cuban troops from Angola and independence for South-West
Africa, also called Namibia.
   South Africa said on Aug. 30 that it had withdrawn the last of
its forces from Angola, leaving rebels of the National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) to fight alone against the
Cubans and government troops.
   UNITA was not included in the peace talks and Savimbi has said
his guerrillas will continue to fight for a power-sharing coalition
with the Marxists.
   Angola won independence from Portugal in 1975 and UNITA lost a
civil war to the Soviet- and Cuban-backed Popular Movement for the
Liberation of Angola. UNITA then began a guerrilla campaign and
Cuba sent troops to help the government.
   Namibia, lying between South Africa and Angola, has been
administered by South Africa since World War I under a mandate by
the defunct League of Nations.
   South Africa has rejected demands by the United Nations that
Namibia be given its independence. A major South African condition
has been withdrawal of Cuban forces from Angola.
   South Africa has said it will withdraw from Namibia by Nov. 1
and allow elections by next June if the Cubans leave Angola.
   UNITA said in a statement distributed in Lisbon, Portugal, that
the rebels had rejected U.S. efforts to persuade them to accept a
period of three years for the removal of the Cuban troops.
   It said the U.S. assistant secretary of state for African
affairs, Chester Crocker, tried to persuade the rebels at a meeting
Aug. 27 at an undisclosed location in Africa to accept a phased
Cuban pullout over a three-year period.
   Savimbi said Saturday at the rebels' headquarters at Jamba in
southern Angola that he supported U.S. efforts to resolve the
13-year-old conflict but complained that Crocker was ``giving all
the cards'' to the Angolan government.
   ``The Cubans do not want to leave Angola, and Crocker knows
that,'' said Savimbi, ``We will continue to fight until the country
is truly free.''
   ``There are now 60,000 Cubans in Angola and they are prepared to
launch attacks within days. The Cubans didn't comer here to wave
goodbye. It is an initiative for an offensive.''
   In Angola, Deputy Foreign Minister Venancio de Moura said Angola
would make concessions at the Brazzaville talks to facilitate the
negotiations but it would not jeopardize its sovereignty and
independence. He did not elaborate on possible concessions,
according to the report by the Angolan news agency ANGOP that was
monitored in Lisbon.
   It said he appealed to UNITA to ``listen to the voice of
reason'' and accept the government proposal that the guerrillas lay
down their weapons and be integrated into society without
recrimination.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
