<DOCNO> AP880905-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 1822EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Draft     09-05 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Draft,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israelis Break Up Draft-Dodger Ring; 16 Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities on Monday arrested two
lieutenant colonels and 14 other soldiers and civilians in raids on
a group that took bribes to help Israelis avoid military service,
Israel radio reported.
   An army statement said authorities began an investigation after
receiving a tip that young people were avoiding active-duty and
reserve service ``in exchange for gratuities and monetary gifts.''
   Such an investigation is rare in Israel, which has a tradition
of a ``citizen army.'' All Israeli Jews are required to serve in
the military _ men for three years and women for two _ and men
remain in the reserves until age 57.
   The army statement gave no indication of how widespread the
scheme was, but Israel television quoted military sources as saying
it may have helped as many as several hundred Israelis avoid
regular and reserve military service.
   Israel television called the scandal unprecedented and said more
arrests were expected.
   The radio report said among the eight soldiers arrested were a
woman and two lieutenant colonels and all were connected to the
recruiting office. It did not identify them.
   The radio and television accounts said the civilians included
several doctors and that ``large sums'' of money were involved, but
did not elaborate.
   Brig. Gen. Emil Elimelech, head of military police, told Israel
television the scheme involved ``false medical documents and
tampering with computers, entering and removing data.''
   Disclosure of the draft-dodging came during the Palestinian
uprising in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel occupied
after the 1967 Middle East war.
   Palestinians have been battling Iraeli rule in the territories
since Dec. 8. The government has responded by sending thousands of
troops into the areas and at least 258 Palestinians and four
Israelis have been killed in the uprising.
   Refusal to serve in the Israeli military is rare but some
soldiers have rejected particular postings. At least 37 soldiers
are in jail for refusing to serve in the occupied territories,
according to Yesh Gvul, an organization of conscientious objectors.
   Elimelech said it was ``absolutely impossible'' to link the
draft-dodging scheme to the uprising.
   Israel radio said the the suspects are to appear for arraignment
Tuesday before a civil judge in Petah Tikva, east of Tel Aviv.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
