<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     09-05 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diplomats Believe Airport Attack Produced Heavy Casualties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A guerrilla rocket attack on Kabul
airport last week may have claimed far more casualties than
reported by official Soviet and Afghan news media, Western
diplomats said Monday.
   The sources, quoting dispatches from Kabul on condition of
anonymity, said two aircraft were confirmed destroyed in the attack
Thursday and 12 helicopters were unaccounted for.
   Moscow's official news agency Tass put casualties at nine dead
and 21 wounded, but the sources said that appeared low.
   ``Western diplomatic observers believe that casualties and
damage to the military areas north of the airport are much higher
than are currently being claimed by Tass,'' one said, but none of
the sources said they had reliable figures.
   Last Thursday the same sources said rebel-fired rockets slammed
into the airport and parts of the capital for more than an hour,
causing ``massive damage'' and igniting an ammunition dump.
   Western diplomats reported seeing one An-12 transport plane on
fire, an unidentified aircraft destroyed and two hangars burned to
the ground.
   They said a helicopter park near the ammunition depot was
largely empty and only 11 military helicopters were observed,
``leaving at least a dozen helicopters unaccounted for.''
   Whether the helicopters had been destroyed or evacuated was not
clear.
   Guerrillas also rocketed the airport Aug. 27, reportedly
destroying one military transport, damaging runways and killing
four people.
   Insurgents have made daring attacks on Kabul in recent weeks as
Soviet troops withdrew, reaching the numerical halfway point on
Aug. 15.
   On Sunday, the guerrillas claimed Soviet forces backed by Afghan
troops had redeployed in the besieged southeastern city of Kandahar.
   Soviet officials said the last Red Army troops left the city
Aug. 7 and Western sources said they could not confirm reports that
any had returned.
   A report from the Associated Press of Pakistan agency said eight
Afghan warplanes bombed a Pakistani village early Monday, killing
one person and wounding eight.
   It identified the bombed village as Bogay in the Dir
administrative district, 140 miles northwest of Islamabad near the
Afghan border.
   Afghan warplanes earlier were reported to have bombed Pakistani
territory last Thursday, killing one villager and wounding seven at
Shabqadar.
   The Islamabad and Kabul governments have had strained relations
since Soviet troops arrived in Afghanistan in 1979 support the
pro-Moscow government. Kabul and Moscow accuse Pakistan and the
United States of aiding the guerrillas.
</TEXT>
