<DOCNO> AP880905-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 1856EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Palau-Shooting     09-05 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Palau-Shooting,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Relatives Handled Gun that Killed President</HEAD>
<HEAD>By HOWARD GRAVES</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow and brother of Palau President Lazarus
E. Salii handled a revolver within minutes after Salii was found
shot to death and before the weapon was turned over to national
police, a government spokesman said.
   The .357-caliber Magnum revolver from which one shot had been
fired was given to police at a hospital by Salii's brother, Carlos,
said spokesman Bonifacio Basilius.
   ``There was hysteria and panic,'' Basilius said. ``They were in
shock. They were not involved in the shooting.''
   The 51-year-old president was the second elected Palau chief
executive to die by violent means in three years.
   Salii was elected in August 1985 to succeed Haruo I. Remeliik,
who was assassinated two months earlier. Three Palau men convicted
at trial in connection with Remeliik's death later were acquitted.
   The Palau government has yet to make public results of an
autopsy performed on Salii 55 hours after his Aug. 20 death at his
home in Koror, the Western Pacific island chain's capital.
   Palau is a 400-mile-long archipelago about 600 miles east of the
Philippines and 4,500 miles southwest of Hawaii. Its nearly 15,000
residents inhabit eight of its 200 islands in a U.N. trusteeship
administered by the United States.
   Salii was a staunch proponent of a proposed compact of free
association that would terminate the trusteeship and make Palau
self-governing.
   The U.S. government is awaiting results of an FBI ballistics
test on the revolver and the spent cartridge, Basilius said in a
telephone interview.
   The tests at the FBI laboratory in Washington might show if
Salii's fingerprints were on the weapon, Basilius said.
   ``We want to know for sure, we want to eliminate any doubt as to
whether there were any other person's fingerprints on the gun,'' he
said. ``We want to be absolutely certain that the bullet came from
that gun.''
   Meanwhile, The Associated Press obtained a copy of an Aug. 24
letter from a high-ranking traditional chief, Ibedul Yutaka M.
Gibbons, in which he addresses the question of whether Salii killed
himself.
   In the letter to Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel, whose
agency is responsible for Palauan affairs, Gibbons wrote that new
President Thomas Remengesau told him the night of Salii's death
that it was a suicide. Gibbons said Remengesau told him Salii
``himself did it at his house.''
   Gibbons said, ``Since the forensic evidence was not finalized by
then, it seems inconceivable that he (Remengesau) would then voice
such an irresponsible conclusion.''
   Gibbons asked Hodel for an investigation into the deaths of
Salii and Remeliik.
   Remengesau was sworn in as president to fill out Salii's
remaining term which ends this year. He was elected vice president
at the special election in which Salii was elected president.
Remengesau also was minister of justice under the two slain
presidents.
   Remengesau is expected to seek the presidency in Palau's Nov. 2
general election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
