<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-OilRig     09-05 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Oil Rig,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Final Piper Alpha Well Plugged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers plugged the last of the 36
wells on the Piper Alpha oil platform and divers now can search for
bodies still missing in the world's worst oil rig disaster, the
operating company said Monday.
   Crews operating from the support vessel Tharos installed the
final cement plug Sunday, Occidental Petroleum said in a statement.
   ``The plugging of the last well on Piper Alpha represents the
successful conclusion of a key stage in the operation to secure the
platform before divers can search the seabed,'' John Brading,
Occidental's chief executive in Britain, said in the statement.
   Brading did not indicate when divers would try to recover the
bodies of workers killed when the platform, about 120 miles off the
Scottish coast, exploded in flames July 6.
   The disaster claimed 167 lives. A police spokesman said Monday
120 bodies remained missing and most were believed to be in the
platform's living quarters, now submerged.
   About 500 feet of the rig's pre-explosion height of 649 feet is
now under water.
</TEXT>
