<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PTL-Bakker     09-05 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL-Bakker,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bakker Still Trying to Raise Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. RIGSBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PTL founder Jim Bakker made an 11th-hour
plea to supporters Monday for help in raising a $3 million down
payment in his bid to return to the ministry he left amid a
sex-and-money scandal.
   ``I'm not going to leave any stone unturned,'' Bakker said in a
telephone interview with The Associated Press. ``I'm not going to
stumble now.''
   Bakker said friends and acquaintances have so far contributed
close to $2 million in cash and letters of credit toward the $3
million he needs by Tuesday.
   He said a group of people is working on raising the remaining $1
million in thousand-dollar pledges and he has set up a trust
account at a Hendersonville, N.C., bank to accept donations. Those
donations would be used only if he and his wife, Tammy Faye,
succeed in purchasing the ministry, he said.
   Bakker said he has raised the money and pledges by word-of-mouth.
   ``We are sort of running our own Labor Day telethon without a
television station,'' he said.
   PTL Bankruptcy Trustee M.C. ``Red'' Benton asked for the money
as a sign of Bakker's ability to follow through on the $165 million
offer he's made for the Heritage USA Christian theme park, a
satellite network and undeveloped property near the Fort Mill
ministry.
   Bakker so far leads the bidding for buying assets of the
ministry that went into bankruptcy soon after he left PTL in March
1987.
   But Benton said Friday he was ``very, very skeptical'' Bakker
could come up with the $3 million letter of credit by Tuesday.
Calls to Benton's Winston-Salem, N.C., home Monday went unanswered.
   After Tuesday, Benton said he would consider other offers to
purchase the ministry's assets. U.S. Bankrupty Judge Rufus Reynolds
has instructed Benton to recommend a buyer by Saturday.
   Bakker attorney Jim Toms said Bakker expects to have the whole
$3 million by Tuesday. But he said he plans to ask Benton to accept
$1 million in cash and a $500,000 letter of credit, so that the
remaining funds could be used to pay immediate operating expenses.
   Bakker said a Midwest bank has agreed to handle the funds from
unidentified Greek investors he says are backing his offer to buy
PTL. He also said he has several other banks are willing to aid his
bid, but he would not identify the banks.
   ``We're almost there,'' Bakker said.
</TEXT>
