<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle-Dynamite 1stLd-Writethru a0621 09-05 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle-Dynamite, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0621,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Arrested At Quayle Rally; Bomb Determined To Be Fake</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with device determined to be fake;
one man in custody, another detained and released; arraignment
scheduled Monday night; No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HAMTRAMCK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man carrying what police thought was a
bomb containing dynamite was arrested Monday shortly before a
campaign appearance by GOP vice presidential candidate Dan Quayle,
officials said.
   The Secret Service said the device, which looked like several
sticks of dynamite wrapped in duct tape, turned out to be fake.
   ``It was made up to look like a bomb. It would have fooled me
and anybody else,'' said Jim Huse, special agent in charge of the
Secret Service field office in Detroit.
   A 38-year-old Hamtramck man was arrested on charges of
interfering with a Secret Service agent and was held at the Secret
Service office pending arraignment later Monday, Huse said. He said
he didn't know the man's reasons for having the device.
   ``We hesitate to speculate until an investigation is complete,''
Huse said.
   Because of the incident, Quayle's departure for Hamtramck from
the Detroit City Airport was delayed and he missed a scheduled walk
in Hamtramck's Polish Day Parade, Huse said.
   Instead, Quayle gave a five-minute speech at the reviewing stand
before leaving.
   The man was seen at a bar near the parade reviewing stand by
someone who saw what looked like a bomb and reported it to police.
The Detroit Police Department's bomb squad removed the device,
which was contained in a paper bag, and determined it was a fake,
Huse said.
   Another man was taken into custody but was released after police
determined he knew nothing of the incident, Huse said.
   Quayle campaign officials referred on questions regarding the
incident to the Secret Service.
</TEXT>
