<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 2034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia     09-05 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Textile Workers, Teachers Strike for Higher Pay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 500 striking textile workers
demonstrated outside Parliament on Monday for higher pay and new
factory management.
   In Serbia, Yugoslavia's largest republic, officials made their
harshest criticism to date of ``Albanian nationalists'' living in
the southern Serbian province of Kosovo, the official news agency
Tanjug reported.
   The texile workers, most of them women, were from the Sloga mill
in Zrenjanin, 40 miles north of Belgrade, which was shut down by a
strike last Wednesday. After assembling outside Parliament they
were directed to the nearby Trade Union Building, where they met
with Social Affairs Minister Janko Obocki.
   ``We are not asking for color TV sets, all we want is bread .. .
for our children,'' worker Snezana Tosko said, according to a
Tanjug report.
   Strikers demanded a doubling of monthly pay, which now averages
$72, and replacement of the plant management.
   Obocki promised the government would find a way to curb
inflation, now running at an annual rate of 190 percent, and
increase real earnings, Tanjug said.
   Teacher strikes prevented the new school year from beginning in
many parts of the country, newspapers reported Monday.
   Nearly 14,000 elementary school students in Mostar, central
Yugoslavia, returned home after finding classrooms locked because
of a walkout by 500 teachers demanding ``significant improvements
of their monthly wages,'' the daily Vecernje Novosti said.
   Other teachers' strikes were reported at Doboj, 125 miles west
of Belgrade, Tanjug said, and in the northern port of Rijeka and
several other Croatian towns.
   About 850 strikes have taken place in Yugoslavia over the past
eight months, according to government figures.
   Officials claim no alternative exists to the austerity program
imposed in conjunction with the International Monetary Fund if
Yugoslavia is to repay its $21 billion foreign debt and revive its
faltering economy.
   Tanjug said Serbia's president, Petar Gracanin, demanded that
more soldiers be sent to restive Kosovo, where 90 percent of the
people are ethnic Albanians, to counter what he called ``terror
unprecedented in postwar Yugoslavia.''
   His speech followed weekend rallies by more than 100,000 people
in four Serbian towns, protesting alleged intimidation by ethnic
Albanians.
   Gracanin, who holds the rank of general in the Yugoslav army,
complained of ``impossible conditions for life and work'' of ethnic
Serbians and Montenegrins in Kosovo, Tanjug said.
   Riots by ethnic Albanians broke out in Kosovo in 1981 and troops
were sent to stop them.
</TEXT>
