<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gandhi-Assassin     09-05 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gandhi-Assassin,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gandhi Assassin Files New Appeal To Avoid Gallows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Sikh policeman convicted in the 1984
assassination of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi asked the Supreme
Court on Monday to reconsider his death sentence.
   Satwant Singh, who faces death by hanging, also asked for a new
trial in the petition he filed with the nation's highest court,
United News of India reported.
   The court on Aug. 3 rejected an earlier appeal of Satwant
Singh's conviction by a lower court. But prisoners who have been
condemned to death are entitled to a final review by the same
judges.
   Kehar Singh, a Sikh government official found guilty of
conspiracy in the assassination, also was sentenced to the gallows
and filed a similiar review petition on Aug. 30.
   If the review petitions are rejected by the high court, the
condemned men can make a final appeal to President Ramaswamy
Venkataraman.
   Mrs. Gandhi was assassinated at her home on Oct. 31, 1984, by
two of her Sikh bodyguards, Satwant Singh and Beant Singh,
apparently in revenge for an army raid she ordered four months
earlier to put down the Sikh revolt in the northern state of Punjab.
   Beant Singh was killed and Satwant Singh injured in a shoot-out
with other security men minutes after the prime minister's slaying.
   Police sub-inspector Balbir Singh, a guard at the prime
minister's residence, had also been convicted and sentenced to
death by lower courts but the conviction was overturned by the
Supreme Court on Aug. 30.
   The defendants are not related. Singh, which means lion in the
Punjabi language, is part of every Sikh male's name by doctrine of
the faith.
   Mrs. Gandhi had ordered the storming of Sikhism's main temple,
the Golden Temple in Amritsar, to clear the shrine of militants
Sikhs campaigning for an independent homeland in the Punjab.
   More than 1,200 people, most of them Sikhs, died in the army
action.
   Sikhs comprise 2 percent of India's 800 million people but are
in majority in Punjab. More than 1,800 people have died in Punjab
this year in violence blamed on Sikh extremists.
</TEXT>
