<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissAmerica     09-05 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miss America,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miss America Production Features `Swimsuit Stroll' and New
Crowning</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XACC1,XACC2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Longtime watchers of the Miss America
Pageant may notice a few changes during Saturday's contest,
including ``swimsuit strolls'' and an ``improved'' final crowning
moment.
   Bill Caligari, the production manager for the Miss America
Pageant, has been testing new ideas in local contests in the past
year.
   Other changes will be a deeper set on the stage and a Y-shaped
runway ``that will give us more flexibility in production
numbers,'' Caligari said during a rehearsal break last week.
   But a more daring innovation is in the swimsuit competition, he
said.
   ``Instead of standing in front of the judges and `ankling up,'
as we called it, we're going to have the girls do a `walking turn'
and not stop at all,'' Caligari said. ``We're de-emphasizing that
`inspection' image that it had for so long.''
   The changes in this year's pageant, scheduled to be televised
nationally by NBC, came largely from ``brainstorming'' sessions
held in the past year after the appointment of the pageant's new
executive director, Leonard Horn.
   Caligari recalled that Horn almost immediately came in and
listed all the things he didn't like about the pageant production
in years past.
   ``It's exciting _ there's a lot of change,'' Caligari said.
``We're going back to the days when the top contestants were asked
questions on stage _ and these won't be `airhead' questions.''
   Horn said the questions ``will be intelligent questions. We're
not going to be testing them on current events, but they won't be
silly questions either.''
   The final moments of the competition will also be different than
in recent years, Caligari said. Traditionally, the fourth, third,
second and first runners-up were announced, and then the new Miss
America was announced from the remaining six contestants.
   This year, the fourth, third and second runners-up will be
announced, and then, to heighten the drama, the remaining six
contestants will be narrowed down to two. The first runner-up will
then be announced, leaving the new Miss America, Caligari said.
   ``The interplay between the two young ladies promises to be
good,'' he said. ``We've tested this in some of the states and it's
worked well.''
   The pageant production will also have one fewer song-and-dance
number, Caligari said.
   ``The show is supposed to focus on 51 young, talented ladies, so
we're including them in all the production numbers,'' he said.
   The time saved from dropping that number will allow the producer
to include brief video spots of the top 10 finalists' interviews
before the judges, Caligari said.
   ``I got the idea to include parts of the contestants' interviews
from the Winter Olympics, when we saw some backstage interviews
before the athlete went out on the ice or snow,'' he said.
   The ``Miss America Moments'' that used to come before each
commercial break _ which simply told viewers what part of the
contest was next _ will be replaced with short spots on what former
state winners are now doing, Caligari said.
   Some of those women include a town mayor, an assistant district
attorney, a Broadway understudy and an aeronautical engineer, he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880905-0130 </DOCNO>
