<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Contras     09-05 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Contras,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Say Nicaragua Mobilizing Troops in Border Province</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sandinista troops are being mobilized
in Jinotega province that borders Honduras, the Nicaraguan rebels'
clandestine Radio Liberation said Monday.
   A Defense Ministry source contacted by The Associated Press said
he had no information about any such mobilization.
   Radio Liberation, in a broadcast monitored here, said, ``A
strong and suspicious mobilization of Sandinista army troops ... to
the interior of that province (Jinotega in northern Nicaragua) was
denounced by campesino families.''
   ``The Sandinistas are sending more patrols to those places,
taking advantage of the fact that the rebels forces have retreated
to the border zones with Honduras,'' it said.
   It is estimated that some 9,000 rebel fighters have returned to
base camps on the Honduran side of the border and about 2,000 are
still operating in Nicaragua.
   The rebels, known as Contras, began returning to their camps in
Honduras in April after Nicaragua's Sandinista government and
Contra leaders agreed to a temporary cease-fire and negotiations
for a permanent truce. The peace talks broke down in June.
   In Honduras the Contras are given U.S.-supplied food and
non-lethal assistance.
   Defense Minister Humberto Ortega said last week Contras who had
left Nicaragua were concentrated near the border.
   He said Sandinista army units are maintaining ``a normal
defense'' along the frontier and claimed they were constantly
harassed by Contras and Honduran troops seeking to provoke a border
conflict.
   Sandinista forces have frequently made sweeps through Jinotega
to dislodge Contras and drive them out of the province.
</TEXT>
