<HEAD>Passenger, Cargo Aircraft Avoid Collision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British passenger jet swerved to avoid colliding
with an Airbus freight plane over the English Channel, Civil
Aviation Authority spokesman Simon Lubin reported Monday.
   He said an Air U.K. Ltd. Boeing 737 jet passed within 1{ miles
horizontally of the Airbus Super Guppy freight plane near Paignton,
southern England, at 12:48 p.m. Sunday. He said the freight plane
was French-registered but he did not know which airline owned it.
   Lubin said both planes were traveling at 20,000 feet, with the
British jet bound from Belfast, Northern Ireland, to the island of
Jersey in the channel, and the French plane bound from Toulouse,
France, to Liverpool, England.
   Air U.K. spokesmen were not immediately available for comment
but the domestic news agency Press Association said the Air U.K.
jet carried 130 passengers. The number of crew aboard either plane
was not reported.
   Lubin said the Joint Airmiss Working Group _ made up of the
Civil Aviation Authority, the British Airline Pilots Association
and the Air Traffic Controllers' Union _ will investigate.
