<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Non-Aligned     09-05 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Non-Aligned,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Non-Aligned Proposal Calls For Sanctions Against Israel, South
Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign ministers preparing Monday for
the non-aligned movement conference discussed proposals that
contain sanctions against Israel and South Africa.
   The five-day conference of foreign ministers is to chart the
101-member organization's role over the next decade. Organizers
said 92 members plan to attend, including 70 foreign ministers.
   President George Vassilou formally opens the three-day
conference on Wednesday.
   But delegates on Monday began considering a 60-page draft
resolution dealing with international problems.
   The draft sharply criticizes Israel and South Africa, echoing
previous sentiments of the movement.
   A copy of the draft notes that since the non-aligned summit
conference last year the situation in the Middle East ``has
worsened considerably, particularly as a result of the actions of
the Israeli occupation forces against the civilian population in
the occupied territories.''
   The draft ``salutes the heroic uprising of the Palestinian
people,'' in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. It says
the Arab uprising in the occupied lands that began Dec. 8 is
``tangible evidence of their determination to have a state of their
own.''
   It demands United Nations sanctions against Israel.
   The draft also expresses ``profound alarm at the sharp
deterioration of the situation in South Africa'' and repeats
previous demands for sanctions against the South African
government, which is controlled by the country's white minority.
   The resolution expresses satisfaction with the July 20
cease-fire between Iran and Iraq and states the U.N.-mediated peace
talks in Geneva should lead to a ``a comprehensive and lasting
solution'' in the 8-year-old war between the Persian Gulf rivals.
   The draft makes no reference to Iraqi use of chemical weapons in
the war.
   Conference sources speaking on condition of anonymity said
Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati is expected to demand
Iraq's condemnation on that issue when he addresses the conference
on Wednesday.
   More than 1,500 police officers, including special
anti-terrorist units, have been assigned to guard the conference
center where the meeting is being held and the delegates' hotels.
</TEXT>
