<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SickSailors     09-05 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sick Sailors,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Recruits Released From Hospital After Mysterious Illness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials still had not determined Monday what
caused a mysterious outbreak that sent 119 young Navy recruits to
the hospital over the weekend with breathing problems, vomiting and
other symptoms.
   Only one of the recruits remained in a hospital after two were
released Monday. The enlisted men from the Naval Training Center
were taken to 10 hospitals in more than 50 ambulances Saturday, and
all but three were released by Sunday night.
   Two more men were released Monday in good condition from Sharp
Cabrillo Hospital, said nursing supervisor Nadine Kalmonson. A
third recruit who was diagnosed with pneumonia was still being held
at the Balboa Hospital, said Navy spokesman Lt. Ken Luchka.
   ``It could have been that one or two people had a viral
infection and got sick, which caused a mass hysteria to the
others,'' Luchka said.
   A hysterical reaction was ``very possible, like in second grade,
when someone vomits and the whole class starts vomiting,'' Luchka
said.
   Navy officials also speculated whether the symptoms may have
been brought on by the extreme heat, heavy smog and strenuous
exercise.
   Environmental health officials, a hazardous materials unit and a
medical unit inspected the barracks but were unable to pinpoint an
explanation for the outbreak, said Petty Officer Pat Neal.
   Hospital tests failed to reveal any poisons in the recruits'
systems, she said.
   The men who returned to the center spent Sunday and Monday
relaxing and were to resume their third week of basic training. The
week's training schedule included classroom sessions and no
physical activity.
</TEXT>
