<HEAD>Run On New Coins Nearly Depletes ``Money From Paradise''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The worlds first triangular $2 coin has
almost sold out in the faraway Cook Islands of the South Pacific
after being advertised as money from paradise, a radio report said
Monday.
   Radio Cooks said investors, mostly from New Zealand, had scooped
up virtually all the 90,000 coins that were minted last year.
   Richard McDonald, director of the Cook Islands Numismatics
Bureau, blamed the run on brochures advertising the coins as money
from paradise.
   The Cook Islands, with a population of about 20,000, is 3,000
kilometers (1,860 miles) northeast of Auckland, New Zealand.
