<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 1306EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-HotelFight Bjt   09-05 0919</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hotel Fight, Bjt,0948</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hotel Magnate Fighting Conglomerate For Hotel</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a cold November day in 1966
when attorney and expectant-father Patrick Kennedy looked out a
downtown hospital window toward the vacant grounds of his alma
mater, St. Mary's University School of Law.
   The international exposition HemisFair was two years away and
Kennedy knew the city needed hotel rooms in the tourist area. So as
his daughter was being delivered, Kennedy devised a plan to turn
the Colonial Spanish-style campus into a luxury hotel with a view
of the popular River Walk.
   Kennedy's gamble in what became La Mansion del Rio paid off.
Tourists crowded into the hotel when it opened in April 1968 and
have been coming ever since.
   Today, Kennedy is fighting for survival and claiming that one of
his lenders, Metropolitan Life Insurance Co., backed him into a
financial corner to steal his hotels for its own hotel management
subsidiary.
   It's a lawsuit the hotel industry is watching carefully.
   Kennedy's attorneys say his $7 billion lawsuit against
Metropolitan could be a test case because it charges that a lender,
in calculated moves, conspired to become a direct competitor with
its borrower.
   ``My biggest problem with this case is trying to understand why
a company with over $100 billion worth of assets and 100 years of
reputable business dealings would stoop to this practice, and that
is the reason I am willing to go through with this lawsuit,''
Kennedy said recently.
   Metropolitan officials deny any wrongdoing and say the case is a
simple contractual agreement that Kennedy broke by not paying his
bills on time.
   ``I think you are seeing an absolute desperation move,'' said
Metropolitan's San Antonio attorney, Seagal V. Wheatley. ``What you
have is a straight-forward loan. Met breached no agreement with Mr.
Kennedy.''
   Wheatley said Kennedy is using the lawsuit to avoid a threatened
bankruptcy.
   Kennedy's lawsuit charges Metropolitan with fraud, duress,
interference, deceptive trade practices, breach of confidential
relationships, unfair dealing and conspiracy in what he claims was
a concerted nationwide effort by Metropolitan and its Phoenix-based
subsidiary, Doubletree Hotels Inc., to take over regional,
profitable hotels at a fraction of their worth.
   The fight is scheduled for another round in court on Sept. 12,
but Metropolitan already claims partial victory from state District
Judge Peter Michael Curry's summary judgment in August that
Metropolitan and Doubletree did not conspire to take over La
Mansion.
   But Kennedy's attorneys are pressing ahead, claiming that
Metropolitan wants to postpone a jury trial until 1989 to drain
Kennedy's resources.
   ``If we can get to a jury and show a jury how Metropolitan was
telling Doubletree that they would be taking over La Mansion
hotels, even before Pat had any problems, and then put the
incredible squeeze on Pat, I think a jury is going to be
offended,'' said Kennedy's attorney, Larry Macon.
   Kennedy was 36 when he transformed the old campus into a luxury
hotel.
   Success fueled expansion desires and Kennedy approached
Metropolitan. In July 1978, the 300-room La Mansion del Norte
opened in San Antonio with an $8.1 million loan from the insurer.
   In 1981, Metropolitan refinanced Kennedy's mortgage to expand
the chain again, increasing his loan to $11.25 million.
   In 1982, Kennedy, in partnership with an investment group,
started construction of La Mansion-Austin financed by Metropolitan
servicing agent American General Insurance Co. The 300-room Austin
hotel opened in April 1984.
   The three hotels, Macon claims, are worth about $80 million.
   Kennedy alleges that between 1981 and 1984, Metropolitan began
thinking of taking over La Mansion after the insurance giant
acquired 20 percent of Doubletree Hotels.
   With the Texas economy on a slide in the mid-1980s, Kennedy's
hotels suffered like others. During that time, Kennedy alleges,
Metropolitan told Doubletree his hotels were in trouble and could
become targets for Doubletree takeovers.
   In July 1986, Doubletree Hotels president Jim Schmidt contacted
him about a franchising plan, but Kennedy declined the offer, he
said.
   That fall Kennedy decided to restructure his management company
and began talking to his lenders. He claims he could not reach a
satisfactory arrangement with Metropolitan.
   ``We reduced his monthly payments by 50 percent and he claims
that we dealt very hard with him,'' said Wheatley.
   The attorney said Kennedy's 1986 restructuring earned him more
than $1 million at a time Kennedy claimed he couldn't make payments
for his north property.
   Kennedy talked with other lenders and agreed to give up
ownership but retain management control of La Mansion del Rio and
La Mansion-Austin.
   In the summer of 1987, unable to find an investor in the hotel,
Kennedy received an extension on his loan payment from
Metropolitan, but by that December, Arnholt declared the loan in
default and threatened foreclosure on La Mansion del Norte.
   The same month, American General Life Insurance posted La
Mansion-Austin for foreclosure and fired Kennedy's management
company. This January, Doubletree began to manage the Austin hotel
after Wheatley claimed it exhausted its search for a management
company.
   In February, Metropolitan planned to foreclose on La Mansion del
Norte and Doubletree employees prepared to move in, but Kennedy
filed suit, obtained a temporary restraining order and kept
Metropolitan from taking over.
   Now, Metropolitan claims that Kennedy is on a free ride, not
having paid a dime for the hotel's debt service since 1986 while
continuing to draw fees for managing the hotel.
   Attorneys for both sides said they're not sure what will happen
on Sept. 12.
</TEXT>
