<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0334</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES With London Shares Closing Up Amid Low Volume</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed higher Monday, helped by
lingering bullish sentiment from U.S. employment figures released
last Friday.
   Price markups by market participants extended a rally begun
Friday on the back of the unemployment data, which showed the U.S.
economy did not expand in August quite as fast as had been expected.
   The data allayed concerns that U.S. interest rates still might
have to rise further to douse an overheating economy.
   Analysts said shares were also moving better because, for the
time being, fears of rising U.K. interest rates have been pushed
into the background. However, market watchers were quick to point
out that participation remained painfully low Monday.
   At the end of trading, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index was up 17.6 points, or 1.00 percent, at 1764.5. The
index opened 10.2 points higher and bounced as much as 20.4 points
higher by mid-morning to its best level of the day.
   Meanwhile, the narrower Financial Times 30-share index was up
14.6 points at 1420.5. Volume was extremely light, with a scant
284.8 million shares changing hands, compared with the 443.8
million shares Friday. Of Monday's total, 192.2 million shares had
been traded by midday.
   Market activity was light in response to a lack of leadership
from Wall Street, which was closed Monday for the Labor Day holiday.
   However, several analysts stressed the market's firm undertone
after Friday's healthy U.S. employment figures for August and a
52-point bounce upwards on the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
   The U.S. Labor Department reported Friday that the U.S. August
unemployment rate rose to 5.6 percent and non-farm payroll jobs
created totaled 219,000. The revised July unemployment rate
remained unchanged at 5.4 percent but the non-farm payroll gain was
revised downward to 200,000 jobs from 283,000 jobs.
   Market expectations had been for a 5.4-percent unemployment rate
and non-farm payrolls at 224,000.
</TEXT>
