<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Argentina-IMF     09-05 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-IMF,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IMF Mission Opens Talks on New Stand-by Loan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief negotiator for the
International Monetary Fund opened talks Monday with government
officials on Argentina's request for a stand-by loan of about $1.2
billion.
   Desmond Lachman was scheduled to meet with Treasury and Central
Bank officials to discuss, among other topics, Argentina's balance
of payments and the anti-inflation plan implemented by President
Raul Alfonsin early last month.
   The IMF funds would be used in part to help Argentina pay
interest on its $56 billion foreign debt. Interest payments on the
debt will total about $4.6 billion this year alone.
   Last week, Argentina reportedly won preliminary approval from
the World Bank for two loans totaling $750 million to reform its
banking system and reorient its trade policy, including the lifting
of restrictions on imports.
   Central Bank President Jose Luis Machinea said early last week
he expected an agreement would be concluded by week's end. However,
no official statement was issued before the World Bank's vice
president for Latin America, Shamid Husain, returned to Washington.
   Lachman is scheduled to be in Argentina for about a week.
   Since Alfonsin took office in December 1983, government policy
has been to finance half the interest payments with Argentine funds
and half with borrowed funds.
   The country's inflation in July exceeded 25 percent. Projections
are that inflation will be at least that high for August, though
Alfonsin and Economy Minister Juan Sourrouille insist the rise in
the cost of living for September will be below 10 percent.
   Treasury Secretary Mario Brodersohn and Central Bank director
Daniel Marx were scheduled to fly to the United States Tuesday to
meet with commercial banks to arrange new loans totaling between
$1.5 billion and $3 billion.
   Argentina's foreign debt is the third highest in the developing
world behind that of Brazil and Mexico. A new IMF agreement would
carry through the end of Alfonsin's term as president, which ends
in December 1989. National elections are set for next May.
</TEXT>
