<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 1420EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WPPSS-Settlement     09-05 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WPPSS-Settlement,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Engineering Firm Settles Two Days Before Federal Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An engineering firm that acted as a
consultant to the Washington Public Supply System on abortive plans
to build two nuclear power plants has settled with bondholders for
$20 million, officials said Monday.
   The settlement between R.W. Beck and Associates of Seattle,
Wash., and bondholders was announced in a statement released by
court-appointed settlement master Junius Hoffman.
   It came two days before the scheduled start of a massive
securities fraud case against WPPSS in federal court here.
   The agreement is subject to approval by U.S. District Court
Judge William Browning, who will preside over the case in which 21
public utilities, two engineering firms and a financial adviser
remain as defendants.
   More than 24,000 bondholders and Chemical Bank of New York, the
trustee for bondholders, allege that the supply system fraudulently
sold $2.25 billion in bonds to build the plants.
   The project was abandoned in 1982 and the supply system declared
default in 1983 after the Washington Supreme Court ruled the public
utilities involved in the project had no authorization to sign
agreements with WPPSS.
   Monday's announcement brought the total settlements so far to
$351 million. Agreement has been reached on an additional $96
million in claims against insurance companies, although the
bondholders must pursue lawsuits to obtain any of that money.
   Last Wednesday the supply system itself settled with the
bondholders for an estimated $3 billion, the cost of the bonds plus
interest.
   Bondholders were expected to see little of that settlement
money, however, because the supply system has few assets to use to
pay back the bonds.
</TEXT>
