<DOCNO> AP880905-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 1423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WPPSSTrial 2ndLd-Writethru   09-05 1079</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-WPPSS Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru,1110</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After Five Years, WPPSS Fraud Case Goes To Trial In Tucson</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 16th graf to update with $351 million in settlements so
far, sted $331 million; picks up 17th graf pvs, ``WPPSS itself
...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>^LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five years and more than $150 million in legal
fees later, a giant fraud case stemming from the biggest default in
the history of the municipal bond market is headed for trial
Wednesday in Tucson, Ariz.
   The litigation in federal court is a consolidation of dozens of
lawsuits filed by bondholders after the Washington Public Power
Supply System's 1983 default on $2.25 billion in bonds sold to
finance construction of two nuclear power plants.
   Though it has remained obscure, the so-called ``Whoops'' case
has won notoriety in legal and financial circles for its size and
complexity.
   Consider:
   _Since about 1980 market defaults have totaled about $5.7
billion. ``Forty percent of that is WPPSS,'' said C. Richard
Lehmann of Miami Lakes, Fla., treasurer of the National WPPSS 4-5
Bondholders Committee.
   _Dozens of attorneys from some 70 law firms, with rates as high
as $400 an hour, have been involved in pre-trial work. Still to be
added to the legal tab are trial costs and the fees of many
attorneys who have worked for five years on contingency.
   _A computerized data-retrieval system for the plaintiffs' side
alone has cost more than $35 million, and it holds 14 million
documents and hundreds of statements by witnesses. The defense is
keeping its system secret.
   _More than 24,000 claims have been filed by an estimated 42,000
bondholders.
   _Defendants, from Wall Street bond underwriting firms to 88
public utilities to law firms and economic advisers, originally
numbered more than 100. Some, including bond underwriters, have
settled outside court for $331 million so far. WPPSS itself was let
out of the suit last week in a surprise move, leaving 21 utilities
and engineering and financial adviser firms as defendants.
   _The trial itself could last up to two years.
   ``The WPPSS case is unique,'' said New York University Professor
Robert Lamb, who has written a book on the supply system's woes.
   ``There is nothing like it. Not only in the dollar amount, but
in the complexity of the involvements of different layers of
government and governmental authority, the complexity of the number
of litigants, claimants, and participants.''
   ``All the major brokerage firms were involved, the (bond) rating
agencies were involved, bond counsel were involved, and different
engineering firms, accounting firms, as well as all layers of
government,'' he said.
   Those complexities aside, however, and the case comes down to
who will pick up the tab for the WPPSS default and the ensuing
legal battle _ bondholders alleging fraud who are stuck with nearly
worthless bonds, or electric utility customers in Washington who
will have to pay higher rates if a decision goes against them.
   ``The public is suing the public,'' Matt Dillon, commissioner of
Snohomish County Public Utility District, a defendant, said in
describing the large groups of potential losers.
   Despite the risk of losing, with the potential of a
multibillion-dollar judgment, settlement efforts have fallen short
as trial looms. The $351 million in settlements so far include $92
million from bond underwriters and most of the rest from insurance.
   WPPSS itself was a relatively minor defendant in the recovery
because others named in the action have more resources to tap.
WPPSS, as part of its settlement, agreed not to contest the future
payment of money to reimburse claimants.
   Left among defendants are only 20 Washington utilities, an
Oregon utility, two engineering firms and a financial advisory
firm. But those 21 utilities held about a two-thirds interest in
the abandoned plants.
   While settlement was encouraged by U.S. District Judge William
Browning, efforts to reach a ``global settlement'' involving all
parties fell short last May when defendants declined to counter a
plaintiff offer of something in excess of $1 billion.
   Without such a settlement, the case could last for years, said
Bob Ratcliffe of Portland, Ore., who retired a year ago as deputy
administrator of the federal Bonneville Power Administration.
   ``It's a lose-lose proposition every day that litigation goes
on,'' he said. ``If the litigation runs its course, it won't be
resolved until well into the next century.''
   For the Northwest, he said, the fighting will continue to have
economic costs and take a toll in ill-will and lack of cooperation
by various energy and governmental entities.
   For the bondholders: ``I don't think any of those living today
will see any money. Maybe their heirs will,'' Ratcliffe said.
   And for attorneys? ``I wish I was still practicing law ... since
this is such a marvelous opportunity,'' Ratcliffe, a lawyer, said
sardonically.
   To bondholders, the case is one of giant fraud and conspiracy,
coupled with a shameless lack of integrity among defendants,
including the Northwest as a region. They say utilities knowingly
entered into faulty agreements with the supply system to build the
two plants, WPPSS Nos. 4 and 5.
   The Washington Supreme Court ruled in June 1983 that Washington
utilities among the 88 participants contracting to build the plants
lacked authority to sign the pacts and did not have to pay.
   Chemical Bank of New York, trustee for bondholders, accelerated
debt payment that August, precipitating the default on the debt.
   Ratepayer representatives say misguided leadership in the 1970s,
faulty projections for energy needs, poor planning and reliance on
experts who were simply wrong were among factors that led the
region astray.
   Utility commissioners wrongly believed the plants would be
needed to prevent power brown-outs and the public would accept big
rate hikes, said Jim Lazar of Olympia, a utility consultant.
   ``They are not on trial for being stupid,'' he said. ``They are
on trial for fraud, and that is different.''
   Others said the mishap at the Three Mile Island nuclear plant in
Pennsylvania and a worldwide economic downturn were both critical.
   Though ratepayers have so far escaped paying for WPPSS Nos. 4
and 5, electric rates have increased five-fold in the Northwest to
pay for three other WPPSS nuclear plants. The rates are assessed
through Bonneville, a federal power marketing agency, which in
effect guaranteed payments for the three plants. That BPA
payment-guarantee was not forthcoming for the terminated plants.
   Trial was moved to Tucson on a motion that a jury of Northwest
residents might be reluctant to return a decision that could raise
their electricity rates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
