<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Venezuela-Gold     09-05 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Venezuela-Gold,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Venezuelan bank plans to open gold-buying office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venezuela, faced with falling oil
export revenue, announced Monday one of its banks will open an
office in the gold-mining region of the country to buy gold
directly from miners.
   Finalven plans to open an office in Guayana, some 400 miles
southeast of Caracas, the official news agency Venpress announced.
   The new office would buy gold directly from miners at world
market rates, said Finalven President Arturo Sosa, a former
Treasury Minister.
   Currently Venezuela is pushing to expand its gold production in
the wake of falling oil export revenue.
   Venezuela is supposed to produce 20 thousand pounds of gold this
year, up from 11 thousand in 1987, according to official estimates.
   Experts estimate that much of the mined gold is smuggled out of
the country in search of better rates. Until recently, there was no
centralized system of aquiring the precious metal from the miners,
who work independently in the primitive region near the Brazilian
border.
   The Venezuelan Central Bank opened an office earlier this year
that also purchases gold directly from the miners.
</TEXT>
