<DOCNO> AP880905-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-88 1549EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Cocoa     09-05 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Cocoa,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prices Discussed at Cocoa Producer-Consumer Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 37-nation International Cocoa Organization
Monday began discussing differences over the support price for
cocoa on the first day of crucial talks on the body's future,
delegates said.
   The ``logical consequence of non-agreement'' will be to consider
implementing plans to start winding down the ICCO, said West German
chief delegate Peter Baron.
   These plans, officially unveiled Monday, call for halting on
Oct. 1 the current levy on internationally traded cocoa _ the
ICCO's main source of finance _ as well as for the selling off of
the ICCO's stockpiles to meet running costs during the coming year.
   Delegates said ending the levy would acknowledge that the ICCO
had no further role to play in supporting prices.
   Already the body lacks enough money to implement a possible new
stockpiling scheme because some producers are behind in payments to
the ICCO, delegates said. The ICCO is owed a total of $70 million,
they said.
   Prices on world markets last week reached their lowest levels in
seven years, reflecting a current world cocoa glut and an absence
of ICCO support operations since February, when intervention buying
was indefinitely suspended.
   The proposed new stockpiling scheme, under which producers would
receive ICCO financing to hold back up to 120,000 metric tons of
cocoa from the market, has been blocked by lack of funds and the
dispute between producers and consumers over the support price for
cocoa.
   Consumers say under the provisions of the price pact
administered by the ICCO a cut in the price was automatically
triggered in March, but this interpretation is rejected by the
producers.
   A special panel set up to resolve the dispute reported to the
ICCO today that it was split 3 to 2 on the issue.
   Its independent Belgian chairman, Jean Parotte, backed the view
of the panel's two consumer members while two producer
representatives backed their side's view, delegates said.
   It is now up to the full ICCO to decide the matter and delegates
said the continued polarization of views made a solution appear
very difficult to attain.
   Baron said even if agreement were possible, consumers would then
press for a further cut in the support price to reflect recent
developments on the market.
   Even then the new stockpiling scheme could not operate without
payment of producer debts to the ICCO, consumer delegates said.
   ``The withholding scheme is linked to the arrears,'' said Baron.
</TEXT>
