<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Distillers 2ndLd-Writethru   09-05 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Distillers, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0456</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBs 2nd graf to insert name of spokesman; ADDs 3 grafs after
5th graf pvs to update with new information; picks up 6th graf pvs,
``The Dublin-...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pernod Ricard SA, the French drinks company, said
Monday it made a friendly takeover offer of 285 million Irish
punts, the equivalent of $412 million, for Irish Distillers Group
PLC to counter a hostile bid by the British liquor group Grand
Metropolitan PLC.
   Pernod claims to have received assurances from 51.8 percent of
the Irish whiskey maker's shareholders to sell their shares to
Pernod, Irish Distillers spokesman Pat Heneghan said.
   Pernod confirmed it had made a 450 pence ($6.50) a share bid,
but declined to comment further before making its official
announcement.
   Trading in shares of Irish Distillers was suspended Monday, at
the company's request, before the official opening of London's
International Stock Market. Shares were suspended at 366 British
pence ($6.17) each, equal to their Friday closing price.
   The suspension followed Grand Metropolitan's announcement late
Sunday that it had raised its takeover bid to 332 million Irish
punts ($480 million) from 253 million punts ($366 million) in
anticipation of Pernod's offer.
   Pernod also said Monday it would challenge the decision of a
British board which regulates mergers and acquisitions to allow
Grand Metropolitan to raise its bid.
   The French company will appeal the decision before Britain's
independent Takeover Panel, whose executive board allowed the
raised bid on Sunday, said Anthony Beevor, director general of the
panel and a member of its executive board.
   In Dublin, Irish Commerce Minister Albert Reynolds said the
takeover situation would also be examined by Ireland's Fair Trades
Commission in terms of its impact on employment, competition and
``the common good.''
   The Dublin-based Irish Distillers said Friday it was holding
talks with Pernod, which has boosted its holding to five percent of
the company's shares from 2.8 percent.
   Pernod has said it would allow Irish Distillers to operate as an
independent component of the Pernod-Ricard group, maintaining the
``integrity of the Irish whiskey industry.''
   The Grand Met bid is worth 525 Irish pence ($7.58) a share, up
from 400 pence ($5.78). Grand Met said Monday it now owns an
8.19-percent stake in Irish Distillers, the largest maker of Irish
whiskey.
   The Irish Distillers' spokesman said Pernod has made an
agreement with FII Fyffes PLC for the 20.04 percent of the shares
it owns.
   Pernod obtained an interim injunction in the Irish High Court
late Sunday preventing Fyffes, an Irish fruit importer, from
selling its shares eleswhere before Wednesday.
   Irish Distillers makes Jameson's, Powers, Paddy and Bushmill's
brands of whiskey.
</TEXT>
